{"title_page": "Pakistani cricket team in England in 2006", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox cricket tour\n| series_name              = Pakistan in England 2006\n| team1_image              = Flag of Pakistan.svg\n| team1_name               = Pakistan\n| team2_image              = Flag of England.svg\n| team2_name               = England\n| from_date                = 1 July\n| to_date                  = 10 September 2006\n| team1_captain            = [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]]\n| team2_captain            = [[Andrew Strauss]]\n| no_of_tests              = 4\n| team1_tests_won          = 0\n| team2_tests_won          = 3\n| team1_tests_most_runs    = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (631)\n| team2_tests_most_runs    = [[Andrew Strauss]] (444)\n| team1_tests_most_wickets = [[Umar Gul]] (18)\n| team2_tests_most_wickets = [[Steve Harmison]] (20)\n| player_of_test_series    = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] and [[Andrew Strauss]]\n| no_of_ODIs               = 5\n| team1_ODIs_won           = 2\n| team2_ODIs_won           = 2\n| team1_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Younis Khan]] (215)\n| team2_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Ian Bell]] (227)\n| team1_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Shoaib Akhtar]] (9)\n| team2_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] (7)\n| player_of_ODI_series     = [[Younis Khan]]\n| no_of_twenty20s              = 1\n| team1_twenty20s_won          = 1\n| team2_twenty20s_won          = 0\n| team1_twenty20s_most_runs    = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] (46)\n| team2_twenty20s_most_runs    = [[Marcus Trescothick]] (53)\n| team1_twenty20s_most_wickets = [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] (3)\n| team2_twenty20s_most_wickets = [[Stuart Broad]] (2)\n| player_of_twenty20_series    = [[Shahid Afridi]]\n}}\nThe [[Pakistan national cricket team]] toured [[England national cricket team|England]] in [[2006 English cricket season|2006]] for a four-match [[Test cricket|Test]] series, a five-match [[One Day International]] series and a single [[Twenty20 International]]. After a drawn first Test, England won the next two matches before being awarded the final match in controversial circumstances; on the fourth day, Pakistan's players were penalised for [[ball tampering]] and refused to resume play after the tea interval, leading the umpires to award England the match and a 3\u20130 series victory. In 2008, the ICC controversially declared the result of the final Test as a draw, altering the scoreline to 2\u20130; however, after criticism, not least by the MCC, this was subsequently reversed in February 2009 and the result restored as an England victory.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\">{{cite news |title=Result U-turn for 2006 Oval Test |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7863464.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 February 2009 |accessdate=1 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n\n\n==Background==\n[[England cricket team|England]] had [[English cricket team in Pakistan in 2005\u201306|toured Pakistan]] the previous winter, with Pakistan winning the three-match Test series 2\u20130 and the five-match ODI series 3\u20132. As a result of the Test series, Pakistan rose two spots in the world Test rankings to be ranked second going into the return tour, and England dropped to third after the 12 July annual update of the [[ICC Test Championship]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Match\n! Venue\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | June\n|-\n| 27 || ODI v Scotland || [[The Grange, Edinburgh (cricket and sports club)|The Grange]]\n|- \n! colspan=\"3\" | July\n|-\n| 1\u20133 || Tour match || [[Grace Road]]\n|-\n| 6\u20139 || Tour match || [[St Lawrence Ground]]\n|-\n| 13\u201317 || 1st Test || [[Lord's]]\n|-\n| 20\u201323 || Tour match || [[County Cricket Ground, Northampton|County Ground, Northampton]]\n|-\n| 27\u201331 || 2nd Test || [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | August\n|-\n| 4\u20138 || 3rd Test || [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]]\n|-\n| 12 || Tour match || [[Denis Compton Oval]]\n|-\n| 13 || Tour match || [[Denis Compton Oval]]\n|-\n| 17\u201321 || 4th Test || [[The Oval]]\n|-\n| 28 || T20I || [[County Cricket Ground, Bristol|County Ground, Bristol]]\n|-\n| 30 || 1st ODI || [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]]\n|- \n! colspan=\"3\" | September\n|-\n| 2 || 2nd ODI || [[Lord's]]\n|-\n| 5 || 3rd ODI || [[The Rose Bowl, Hampshire|The Rose Bowl, Southampton]]\n|-\n| 8 || 4th ODI || [[Trent Bridge]]\n|-\n| 10 || 5th ODI || [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground|Edgbaston]]\n|}\n\n==Squads==\n{| style=\"width:100%\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"width:46%\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Pakistan<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/squad/249959.html Pakistan Test Squad], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref>\n|-\n! Name\n! style=\"width:20%\"| Style\n! Domestic team(s)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] [[captain (cricket)|c]] || RHB, [[Slow left arm|SLA]] || [[Multan cricket team|Multan]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Kamran Akmal]] [[wicketkeeper|wk]] || RHB || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Lahore Ravi cricket team|Lahore Ravi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Lahore Ravi cricket team|Lahore Ravi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Danish Kaneria]] || RHB, [[Leg break|LB]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]], [[Karachi Urban cricket team|Karachi Urban]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Faisal Iqbal]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA]], [[Karachi Harbour cricket team|Karachi Harbour]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Iftikhar Anjum]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Zarai Taraqiati Bank Limited|ZTBL]], [[Islamabad cricket team|Islamabad]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Imran Farhat]] || LHB, [[Leg break|LB]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]], [[Lahore Shalimar cricket team|Lahore Shalimar]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] || LHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Sialkot cricket team|Sialkot]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Hafeez]] || RHB, [[Off break|OB]] || [[Sui Northern Gas Pipelines Limited|SNGPL]], [[Faisalabad cricket team|Faisalabad]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Sami]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RF]] || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Karachi Harbour cricket team|Karachi Harbour]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] || RHB || [[Water and Power Development Authority|WAPDA]], [[Lahore Ravi cricket team|Lahore Ravi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Naved-ul-Hasan]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RMF]] ||[[Sialkot cricket team|Sialkot]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Salman Butt]] || LHB, [[Off spin|OB]] || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Lahore Shalimar cricket team|Lahore Shalimar]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Samiullah Khan Niazi]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|LMF]] || [[Sui Northern Gas Pipelines Limited|SNGPL]], [[Faisalabad cricket team|Faisalabad]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Shahid Afridi]] || RHB, [[Leg break|LBG]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Shahid Nazir]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]], [[Faisalabad cricket team|Faisalabad]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Shahid Yousuf]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RMF]] || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Sialkot cricket team|Sialkot]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Shoaib Akhtar]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RF]] || [[Rawalpindi cricket team|Rawalpindi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Shoaib Malik]] || RHB, [[Off break|OB]] || [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA]], [[Sialkot cricket team|Sialkot]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Taufeeq Umar]] || LHB, [[Off break|OB]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]], [[Lahore Ravi cricket team|Lahore Ravi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Umar Gul]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA]], [[Peshawar cricket team|Peshawar]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Younis Khan]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]], [[Peshawar cricket team|Peshawar]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Naved-ul-Hasan]] withdrew before the series started, and was replaced by Samiullah Khan Niazi. He returned to the squad for the fourth Test, but was not selected.<ref name=Test4>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/story/256548.html Hafeez to open as Shoaib is ruled out], by Andrew Miller, Cricinfo, retrieved 18 August 2006</ref>\nOn 15 July, [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] and [[Shoaib Malik]] returned home, and were replaced by Iftikhar Anjum and Taufeeq Umar. Iftikhar Anjum left several days later following his father's death, with no replacement called up.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/story/254387.html Rao Iftikhar leaves squad after father's death], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref>\n\nSalman Butt, Samiullah Khan Niazi and Taufeeq Umar travelled home before the fourth Test, and [[Mohammad Hafeez]] was called up.<ref name=Test4/>\n\nFaisal Iqbal, Mohammad Sami and Shahid Nazir returned home after the Test series, and were replaced by Shahid Yousuf and Shoaib Malik.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/squad/257034.html Pakistan One-Day Squad], from Cricinfo, retrieved 24 August 2006</ref> Mohammad Asif and Shoaib Akhtar only played in the ODI series, having returned from injury.\n|}\n| style=\"width:8%\"|\n| style=\"width:46%\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | England<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/squad/252784.html England Squad \u2013 1st Test], retrieved from Cricinfo 31 July 2006</ref><ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/squad/254245.html England Squad \u2013 2nd Test], retrieved from Cricinfo 31 July 2006</ref>\n|-\n! Name\n! style=\"width:20%\"| Style\n! Domestic team\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Andrew Strauss]] [[captain (cricket)|c]] || LHB, [[Fast bowling|LM]] || [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Geraint Jones]] [[wicketkeeper|wk]] || RHB || [[Kent County Cricket Club|Kent]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Chris Read]] [[wicketkeeper|wk]] || RHB|| [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Ian Bell]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Stuart Broad]] || LHB, [[Fast bowling|RMF]] || [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Rikki Clarke]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Paul Collingwood]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Alastair Cook]] || LHB, [[Slow left arm|SLA]] || [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Jamie Dalrymple]] || RHB, [[Off break|OB]] || [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Darren Gough]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RF]] || [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Steve Harmison]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RF]] || [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Matthew Hoggard]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Ed Joyce]] || LHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Sajid Mahmood]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Graham Onions]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Monty Panesar]] || LHB, [[Slow left arm|SLA]] || [[Northamptonshire County Cricket Club|Northamptonshire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Kevin Pietersen]] || RHB, [[Off break|OB]] || [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Liam Plunkett]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RMF]] || [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Marcus Trescothick]] || LHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Michael Yardy]] || LHB, [[Slow left arm|SLA]] || [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Dalrymple was only selected for the second Test, and later withdrawn along with Plunkett as the squad was cut down from 14 to 12. \nRead was added for the third Test after Jones suffered a finger injury, though the English chairman of selectors said that \"the decision was taken regardless of the injury to Geraint's finger\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/current/story/255067.html Read called up as England drop Jones], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref> He also played the fourth Test.\n\nBroad, Clarke, Gough, Joyce and Yardy were only selected for the ODI squad. Hoggard and Panesar were only selected for the Test squad.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/current/story/257602.html Gough and Broad in England squad], from Cricinfo, retrieved 24 August 2006</ref>\n\nGough withdrew after the second ODI with a shin injury, and Onions was called up to replace him.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/england/5310512.stm Injured Gough replaced by Onions], from BBC, retrieved 4 September 2006</ref>\n|}\n|}\n\n==Tour matches==\n===First-class: Leicestershire v Pakistanis===\n{{Test match\n| date = 1\u20133 July 2006\n| team1 = [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 315/9[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (81 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Dinesh Mongia]] 129 (234)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Mohammad Sami]] 3/53 (17 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 304/5[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (85 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Imran Farhat]] 81 (132)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Nick Walker (cricketer)|Nick Walker]] 3/47 (24 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 191 (43 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Tom New]] 67 (108)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 4/32 (11 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 207/2 (40.2 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Shoaib Malik]] 110 (124)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Chris Liddle]] 2/27 (10 overs)\n| result = Pakistanis won by 8 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225259.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Grace Road]], [[Leicester]]\n| umpires = [[Neil Bainton]] (Eng) and [[John Holder (cricketer)|John Holder]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistanis won the toss and elected to field.\n| notes = [[Matthew Boyce]] (Leics) made his first-class debut.\n}}\n\n===First-class: Pakistanis v England A===\n{{Test match\n| date = 1\u20133 July 2006\n| team1 = [[England Lions cricket team|England A]] {{flagicon|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 595/9[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (173 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Chris Read]] 150[[Not out|*]]\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 4/158 (48 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 242 (73.1 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Faisal Iqbal]] 82 (150)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Jamie Dalrymple]] 4/61 (24 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 153/1[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (44.1 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Alastair Cook]] 80 (128)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Imran Farhat]] 1/46 (20 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 154/2 (50 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Salman Butt]] 50 (90)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = \n| result = Match drawn\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225260.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Grace Road]], [[Leicester]]\n| umpires = [[Daryl Hair]] (Aus) and [[Richard Illingworth]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistanis won the toss and elected to field.\n| notes = In Pakistan's second innings, both batsmen retired out.\n}}\n\n===First-class: Northamptonshire v Pakistanis===\n{{Test match\n|date = 20\u201322 July 2006\n| team1 = [[Northamptonshire County Cricket Club|Northamptonshire]]\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 269/3[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (62.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Stephen Peters]] 142 (195)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Samiullah Khan (cricketer)|Samiullah Khan]] 2/35 (8.3 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 250/9[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (64.5 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 202 (330)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[David Wigley]] 5/77 (22.5 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 140 (38.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Ben Phillips (cricketer)|Ben Phillips]] 39 (58)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Shahid Nazir]] 3/33 (7 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 160/3 (40.2 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Salman Butt]] 84 (120)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Bilal Shafayat]] 2/25 (7 overs)\n| result = Pakistanis won by 7 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225261.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Wantage Road]], [[Northampton]]\n| umpires = [[Nick Cook (cricketer)|Nick Cook]] (Eng) and [[Neil Mallender]] (Eng)\n| toss = Northamptonshire won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\n\n===One-day: Pakistanis vs West Indies A===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 12 August 2013\n| time = 10:45\n| team1 = [[West Indies A cricket team|West Indies A]] {{flagicon|WIN}}\n| score1 = 214/4 (40 overs)\n| score2 = 123/3 (22 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| runs1 = [[Lendl Simmons]] 108[[not out|*]] (122)\n| wickets1 = [[Samiullah Khan (cricketer)|Samiullah Khan]] 3/30 (6 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Imran Farhat]] 62[[not out|*]] (43)\n| wickets2 = [[Richard Kelly (cricketer, born 1984)|Richard Kelly]] 2/27 (5 overs)\n| result = No result\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/engine/match/225262.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Denis Compton Oval]], [[Shenley, Hertfordshire|Shenley]]\n| umpires = [[Trevor Jesty]] (Eng) and [[Richard Kettleborough]] (Eng)\n| motm = \n| toss = Pakistanis won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = Rain meant the match was reduced to 40 overs a side. Further rain ended the Pakistanis' innings after 22 overs.\n| notes = \n}}\n\n===List A: Pakistanis vs West Indies A===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 13 August 2013\n| time = 10:45\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score1 = \n| score2 =\n| team2 = {{flagicon|WIN}} [[West Indies A cricket team|West Indies A]] \n| result = Match abandoned without a ball bowled\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/255928.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Denis Compton Oval]], [[Shenley, Hertfordshire|Shenley]]\n| umpires = [[Trevor Jesty]] (Eng) and [[Richard Kettleborough]] (Eng)\n| toss = No toss.\n| rain = No play was possible due to a waterlogged pitch.\n}}\n\n==Test series==\n===1st Test===\n{{Test match\n|date = 13\u201317 July 2006\n|team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 528/9[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (158.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Paul Collingwood]] 186 (327)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 3/119 (52 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 445 (119.3 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 202 (330)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Steve Harmison]] 4/94 (29.3 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 296/8[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (84.5 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Andrew Strauss]] 128 (214)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 3/77 (30 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 214/4 (73 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] 56 (111)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Monty Panesar]] 2/60 (27 overs)\n| result = Match drawn\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225255.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Lord's]], London\n| umpires = [[Simon Taufel]] (Aus) and [[Steve Bucknor]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (Pak)\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\nEngland made an opening stand 60 runs before losing their first two wickets in quick succession, as [[Marcus Trescothick]] fell, followed an over later by captain [[Andrew Strauss]]. [[Kevin Pietersen]] was the next man out, adding just 28 runs for the third wicket, but [[Alastair Cook]] and [[Paul Collingwood]] both reached centuries on the way to a fourth-wicket partnership of 233 runs before Cook was out for 105. Collingwood top-scored in the innings with 186, and [[Ian Bell]] also managed an unbeaten 100 before England immediately declared on 528/9 with half a session left in the second day's play.\n\n[[Steve Harmison]] took two wickets in three balls before the close of play, helping England reduce Pakistan to 68/4 early on the third day; however, [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer)|Mohammad Yousuf]] and captain [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] added 173 runs for the fifth wicket, and [[Kamran Akmal]] also made a half-century, reaching 58 before he was caught behind off the bowling of [[Kevin Pietersen]]. Despite partners falling around him, [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer)|Mohammad Yousuf]] managed to bat on to a double-century before he was caught behind off Harmison to close the innings \u2013 Harmison finished with figures of 4/94.\n\nEngland began the process of building on their 83-run lead early on the fourth day, but Strauss' 128 was the only notable score as they amassed 296 runs before declaring early on the final day, giving Pakistan a target of 380 to chase in 73 overs. [[Salman Butt]] fell to the first ball of the innings from Hoggard, followed by [[Imran Farhat]] to leave the tourists at 33/2; however, scores of 48 from [[Faisal Iqbal]] and Mohammad Yousuf got them to 141/4, before Inzamam-ul-Haq and [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] batted out the last session for 73 to secure a draw.\n\n===2nd Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 27\u201329 July 2006\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK}}\n| team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 119 (38.4 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Younis Khan]] 44 (62)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Steve Harmison]] 6/19 (13 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 461/9[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (133 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Alastair Cook]] 127 (260)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Umar Gul]] 3/96 (28 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 222 (67.1 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Younis Khan]] 62 (119)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Steve Harmison]] 5/57 (18.1 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = \n| runs-team2-inns2 = \n| wickets-team2-inns2 = \n| result = England won by an innings and 120 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225256.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]], Manchester\n| umpires = [[Simon Taufel]] (Aus) and [[Steve Bucknor]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Steve Harmison]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\nWith [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]]'s run of half-centuries against England finally stopped, as he was caught by [[Kevin Pietersen]] off [[Steve Harmison]]'s bowling for a duck, England recorded an innings victory over Pakistan to take a 1\u20130 lead into the third Test. In the first innings, Pakistan lost the last eight wickets for 29 to post 119 with no batsmen making a half-century; England surpassed that score for the loss of two wickets, and with [[Alastair Cook]] and [[Ian Bell]] both making hundreds (127 and 106* respectively), England could eventually declare near the end of day two having made 461. It took England 63 overs to clean up, with Harmison and [[Monty Panesar]] sharing the ten wickets evenly (the only wicket takers in both innings) with the help of wicket keeper [[Geraint Jones]], who caught five despite his fractured finger. Panesar took his second five-wicket-haul in three months, and was praised by opposition coach [[Bob Woolmer]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/england/5229112.stm Panesar tipped for greatness], from BBC, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref>\n\n===3rd Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 4\u20138 August 2006\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 515 (123 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Kevin Pietersen]] 135 (169)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Umar Gul]] 5/123 (29 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 538 (141.4 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 192 (261)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Monty Panesar]] 3/127 (47.4 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 345 (88.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Andrew Strauss]] 116 (171)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Shahid Nazir]] 3/32 (14 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 155 (47.5 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Younis Khan]] 41 (83)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Sajid Mahmood]] 4/22 (8 overs)\n| result = England won by 167 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225257.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]], Leeds\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Darrell Hair]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\nAfter their innings defeat in the second test, Pakistan dropped [[Shahid Afridi]] and [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]], and had to swap [[Imran Farhat]] out due to injury. They brought in [[Salman Butt]] and [[Taufeeq Umar]] to open the innings, plus the bowling of [[Shahid Nazir]]. England only made one change, which was to swap the struggling wicketkeeper [[Geraint Jones]] for [[Chris Read]]. The wicketkeeper position had been the subject of much debate. Read was perceived as the better keeper, although Jones\u2019 batting skills were considered to be superior. However, Jones had not scored a significant innings for some time and Read was given an opportunity to impress for the first time since the West Indies tour of 2004.\n\nThe first day of the test prompted some interesting incidents as England won the toss and batted first. In the morning, there were three rogue decisions from the umpires (who had been testing the use of earpieces to communicate with off-field officials); in the afternoon Kevin Pietersen left the field in bizarre circumstances, and Pakistan responded with 11 overs of very mediocre bowling, using their opening batsmen to bowl during the period before the second new ball was due.\n\nIn amongst all this, Pietersen scored his 5th test century, and helped propel England to 347/6 by the end of the day. England continued on day 2, with [[Ian Bell]] posting his third consecutive test century, and the lower order added useful runs before England were bowled out for 515.\n\nPakistan's openers once again struggled, and they fell quickly to leave the tourists on 36/2. However, the experienced combination of [[Younis Khan]] and [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] then combined to produce the largest partnership for Pakistan against England of 363 for the third wicket. They batted well into the afternoon session of the third day, before Yousuf gloved [[Stephen Harmison]] through to the keeper having scored 192.\n\nPakistan then lost some of their advantage in a bizarre passage of play leading up to the tea interval. Younis was run out on 173, [[Faisal Iqbal]] fell lbw to his first delivery faced (giving [[Paul Collingwood]] his first test wicket), and [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] lost his wicket in a comical way, overbalancing while attempting to sweep a [[Monty Panesar]] delivery and falling onto his stumps.\n\nThe lower order batsmen tried to accelerate the scoring, but lost regular wickets in the process, and Pakistan were finally bowled out for 538.\n\nEngland's second innings started well, with the openers putting on 158 for the first wicket. [[Andrew Strauss]] went on to score 116, and [[Chris Read]] scored 55 down the order, but the other wickets fell quite regularly as England attempted to set up a position where they could push for a win on the final day. Pakistan's bowling attack shared the wickets between them, and eventually bowled England out for 345. Pakistan needed 323 runs on the final day to win.\n\nEngland's bowlers performed well on the final day, and took 5 wickets in the first session ensuring the 323 run target was well out of Pakistan's reach. The run out of [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] for a single figure score was a key moment in the innings \u2013 in fact, Pakistan lost 3 of their top order batsmen to run outs during the game. [[Sajid Mahmood]] struck twice in an over shortly before lunch to remove [[Faisal Iqbal]] and [[Kamran Akmal]], and would go on to record test best figures of 4/22.\n\n[[Monty Panesar]] also demonstrated his promising talent, taking 3 wickets in the second innings to follow up on 3 wickets in the first, on a pitch not typically associated with assisting spinners. His dismissal of [[Younis Khan]] during the afternoon session was spectacular, with a wonderfully flighted delivery that just clipped the bail of the off stump.\n\nFrom this point, it was a matter of time before England took the honours.\n\nAs a result of a rib injury obtained during the course of the Test (and determined to be an ''internal'' injury rather than an ''external'' one<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5253966.stm | work=BBC News | title=Rib injury keeps Inzamam waiting | date=7 August 2006}}</ref>) the Pakistan Captain, [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]], was unable to bat for 4h20m in the Pakistan 2nd innings, or until the fall of the 5th wicket (whichever came first). As England took five wickets in the first session of the last day, he was able to come in at number 7 in the order. His wicket was eventually the last to fall, being stumped off the bowling of [[Monty Panesar]], and Pakistan were all out for 155.\n\nEngland won the match by 167 runs, and took an unassailable 2\u20130 lead in the series, with one left to play.\n\n===4th Test===\n{{main|2006 ball-tampering controversy}}\n{{Test match\n| date = 17\u201320 August 2006\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 173 (53.2 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Alastair Cook]] 40 (69)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Umar Gul]] 4/46 (15.2 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 504 (129.5 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 128 (236)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Monty Panesar|MS Panesar]] 4/125 (30.5 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 298/4 (72 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Kevin Pietersen]] 96 (114)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Shahid Nazir]] 1/26 (8 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 =\n| runs-team2-inns2 =\n| wickets-team2-inns2 =\n| result = England awarded the match<br />(opposition refused to play)\n| venue = [[The Oval]], London\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Darrell Hair]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)<br />Players of the Series: [[Andrew Strauss]] (Eng) and [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (Pak)\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225258.html Scorecard]\n| notes = Match abandoned on day 4 because Pakistan refused to resume play after tea.\n| rain = \n}}\nPakistan made three changes to their side for the final test. The uncertainty of the opening pair continued, with [[Salman Butt]] and [[Taufeeq Umar]] being dropped in favour of [[Imran Farhat]] and [[Mohammad Hafeez]]. The tourists' bowling ranks were boosted by the return of [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]], for whom [[Mohammad Sami]] made way.\n\nPakistan won the toss and chose to field in cloudy conditions. This proved to be a good decision, as Pakistan's seamers [[Umar Gul]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] took eight wickets between them on the way to bowling England out for 173. Asif in particular caused problems for England's batsmen, and left people wondering what the outcome of the series would have been had he not been injured for the earlier tests.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nLate on day 1, Pakistan began their reply confidently, and their fourth opening partnership combination of the series proved to be the most successful one. Hafeez hit some good shots before retiring hurt with a knee problem. He would return to complete his innings and score 95, while Farhat scored 91. England's poor first day was complete when they dropped [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] twice before he reached double figures. He went on to score 128, his third century of the series.\n\nPakistan continued their dominance of the match on day 2, with the close of play score at 336/3, a lead of 163. On day 3, England finally managed to start taking wickets in between frequent rain and bad light interruptions, but they were not able to curtail Pakistan's scoring. [[Faisal Iqbal]] ended on 58 not out, his first contribution in the series. Pakistan were finally bowled out for 504, a lead of 331.\n\n[[Marcus Trescothick]] was dismissed early in England's second innings, in what would be his last test match appearance for England to date. [[Andrew Strauss]] and [[Alastair Cook]] then progressed the score to 78/1 at the close of play.\n\nThe (what would prove to be eventful) fourth day began with Strauss and Cook continuing on the improved batting performance before Strauss fell lbw to [[Danish Kaneria]] with the score on 115. [[Kevin Pietersen]] came in and played an aggressive innings, hitting 96 from 114 deliveries, and only falling when he chased a wide delivery in an attempt to bring up his century.\n\nThe dismissal of Cook for 83 off the bowling of [[Umar Gul]], with a delivery of reverse swing, resulted in umpires [[Darrell Hair]] and [[Billy Doctrove]] calling a halt to play so a set of used balls could be brought out to the middle. England were awarded 5 penalty runs and this event was the catalyst for the subsequent refusal to continue the match after tea by the Pakistan team. Based on the laws of cricket, the umpires declared Pakistan to have forfeited the game and [[Result_(cricket)#Awarded|awarded]] England the win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5268886.stm |title=Lengthy talks fail to save Test |publisher=BBC |date=20 August 2006 |accessdate=20 August 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/5269906.stm |title=Inzamam charged in cheating row |publisher=BBC |date=21 August 2006 |accessdate=21 August 2006 }}</ref> The ICC later changed the result of the match to a draw,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/359329.html |title=ICC changes Oval forfeiture to draw |publisher=ESPN Sports Media |date=3 July 2008 |accessdate=21 September 2011 }}</ref> and then later reversed this decision on 1 February 2009.<ref name=\"award2009\">{{cite news|title=Cricket: England awarded Oval Test 'win' against Pakistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/feb/01/england-pakistan-oval|accessdate=8 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n==T20 series==\n===Only T20I===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 28 August 2006\n| time = 15:00\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 144/7 (20 overs)\n| score2 = 148/5 (17.5 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Marcus Trescothick]] 53 (36)\n| wickets1 = [[Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzaq]] 3/30 (4 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] 46 (40)\n| wickets2 = [[Stuart Broad]] 2/35 (4 overs)\n| result = Pakistan won by 5 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225263.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Nevil Road]], [[Bristol]]\n| umpires = [[Peter Hartley (cricketer)|Peter Hartley]] and [[Nigel Llong]]\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to bat.\n| rain = [[Ian Bell]], [[Stuart Broad]] and [[Michael Yardy]] (all Eng) made their T20I debuts.\n| notes = This was Pakistan's first T20I match.\n}}\n\nPakistan won the match by five wickets. After bowling out four of England's upper order batsmen for fewer than 20 runs between them, Pakistan secured a comfortable win aided by Shahid Afridi who struck 28 off just 10 balls (22 of these in a single over).\n\n==England ODI series==\n===1st ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 30 August 2006\n| time = 14:30\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 202 (49.2 overs)\n| score2 = 46/1 (7 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Ian Bell]] 88 (117)\n| wickets1 = [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] 3/28 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] 18[[Not out|*]] (23)\n| wickets2 = [[Stuart Broad]] 1/14 (3 overs)\n| result = No result\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225245.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]], [[Cardiff]]\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Ian Gould]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = Pakistan innings reduced to 32 overs due to rain.\n}}\n\n===2nd ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 2 September 2006\n| time = 10:15\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 166 (39.1 overs)\n| score2 = 169/3 (36.4 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Rikki Clarke]] 39 (47)\n| wickets1 = [[Shoaib Akhtar]] 4/28 (8 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Younis Khan]] 55 (89)\n| wickets2 = [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] 2/11 (8 overs)\n| result = Pakistan won by 7 wickets ([[Duckworth\u2013Lewis method|D/L]])\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225246.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Lord's]], [[London]]\n| umpires = [[Mark Benson]] and [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Shoaib Akhtar]] (Pak)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = Late start due to rain reduced both innings to 46 overs; further rain reduced Pakistan innings to 40 overs.\n}}\n\n===3rd ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 5 September 2006\n| time = 14:30\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 271/9 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 274/8 (48.5 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Jamie Dalrymple]] 62 (78)\n| wickets1 = [[Naved-ul-Hasan]] 4/57 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Younis Khan]] 101 (109)\n| wickets2 = [[Stuart Broad]] 3/57 (10 over)\n| result = Pakistan won by 2 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225247.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]], [[Southampton]]\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Nigel Llong]]\n| motm = [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n}}\nShoaib Akhtar was in the spotlight after television cameras caught him working on the ball. The pictures appeared to show Akhtar flicking his thumb at the ball. However, [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] referee [[Mike Procter]] analysed the TV footage and decided there was no case to answer on behalf of the Pakistani team.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5312576.stm Match report] accessed 6 September 2006</ref>\n\n===4th ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 8 September 2006\n| time = 14:30\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK}}\n| score1 = 235/8 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 237/2 (46.2 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n| runs1 = [[Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzaq]] 75[[Not out|*]] (72)\n| wickets1 = [[Michael Yardy]] 3/24 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Ian Bell]] 86[[Not out|*]] (111)\n| wickets2 = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] 1/21 (4.2 overs)\n| result = England won by 8 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225248.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Trent Bridge]], [[Nottingham]]\n| umpires = [[Mark Benson]] and [[Daryl Harper]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Ian Bell]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to bat.\n| notes = [[Michael Yardy]] (Eng) made his ODI debut.\n}}\n\n===5th ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 10 September 2006\n| time = 10:15\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK}}\n| score1 = 154/9 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 155/7 (31 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n| runs1 = [[Younis Khan]] 47 (80)\n| wickets1 = [[Jamie Dalrymple]] 2/13 (6 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Andrew Strauss]] 35 (41)\n| wickets2 = [[Shahid Afridi]] 2/14 (5 overs)\n| result = England won by 3 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225249.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Edgebaston]], [[Birmingham]]\n| umpires = [[Ian Gould]] (Eng) and [[Daryl Harper]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Sajid Mahmood]] (Eng)<br>'''Man of the Series''': [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to field.\n}}\n\n==Scotland ODI series==\n===Only ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 27 June 2006\n| time = 10:45\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|SCO}}\n| score1 = 203/8 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 205/5 (43.5 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Ryan Watson (cricketer)|Ryan Watson]] 80 (85)\n| wickets1 = [[Shoaib Malik]] 3/35 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 83[[Not out|*]] (113)\n| wickets2 = [[Paul Hoffmann (cricketer)|Paul Hoffmann]] 3/22 (10 overs)\n| result = Pakistan won by 5 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/240777.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Grange Cricket Club Ground]], [[Edinburgh]]\n| umpires = [[Daryl Hair]] (Aus) and [[Subhash Modi]] (Ken)\n| motm = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (Pak)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| notes = [[Paul Hoffmann (cricketer)|Paul Hoffmann]], [[Dougie Lockhart]], [[Ross Lyons]], [[Neil McCallum (cricketer)|Neil McCallum]], [[Neil MacRae]], [[Dewald Nel]], [[Colin Smith (Scottish cricketer)|Colin Smith]] and [[Ryan Watson (cricketer)|Ryan Watson]] (all Sco) made their ODI debuts.\n}}\nPakistan won the match by five wickets, after Scotland lost four wickets in the first eight overs and then four more in the remaining 42. [[Ryan Watson (cricketer)|Ryan Watson]] and [[Neil McCallum (cricketer)|Neil McCallum]] put on 116 for the fifth wicket, an ODI record partnership for [[Scotland national cricket team|Scotland]], who played their first ODI for seven years.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/SCOT/BATTING/ODI_PARTNERSHIP_RECORDS_SCOT.html ODI Partnership Records for Scotland], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref> Their innings also doubled the number of ODI fifties scored for Scotland.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/SCOT/BATTING/ODI_BAT_HIGH_INNS_SCORES_SCOT.html ODI Career Highest Individual Scores], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* ''Playfair Cricket Annual''\n* ''Wisden Cricketers Almanack 2007''\n\n==External sources==\n[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Seasons/Tours_2006.html CricketArchive]\n\n{{International cricket in 2006}}\n{{International cricket tours of Pakistan}}\n{{International cricket tours of England}}\n\n[[Category:Pakistani cricket tours of England|2006]]\n[[Category:2006 in English cricket]]\n[[Category:International cricket competitions in 2006]]\n[[Category:Cricket controversies]]\n[[Category:2006 in Pakistani cricket]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox cricket tour\n| series_name              = Pakistan in England 2006\n| team1_image              = Flag of Pakistan.svg\n| team1_name               = Pakistan\n| team2_image              = Flag of England.svg\n| team2_name               = England\n| from_date                = 1 July\n| to_date                  = 10 September 2006\n| team1_captain            = [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]]\n| team2_captain            = [[Andrew Strauss]]\n| no_of_tests              = 4\n| team1_tests_won          = 0\n| team2_tests_won          = 3\n| team1_tests_most_runs    = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (631)\n| team2_tests_most_runs    = [[Andrew Strauss]] (444)\n| team1_tests_most_wickets = [[Umar Gul]] (18)\n| team2_tests_most_wickets = [[Steve Harmison]] (20)\n| player_of_test_series    = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] and [[Andrew Strauss]]\n| no_of_ODIs               = 5\n| team1_ODIs_won           = 2\n| team2_ODIs_won           = 2\n| team1_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Younis Khan]] (215)\n| team2_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Ian Bell]] (227)\n| team1_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Shoaib Akhtar]] (9)\n| team2_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] (7)\n| player_of_ODI_series     = [[Younis Khan]]\n| no_of_twenty20s              = 1\n| team1_twenty20s_won          = 1\n| team2_twenty20s_won          = 0\n| team1_twenty20s_most_runs    = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] (46)\n| team2_twenty20s_most_runs    = [[Marcus Trescothick]] (53)\n| team1_twenty20s_most_wickets = [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] (3)\n| team2_twenty20s_most_wickets = [[Stuart Broad]] (2)\n| player_of_twenty20_series    = [[Shahid Afridi]]\n}}\nThe [[Pakistan national cricket team]] toured [[England national cricket team|England]] in [[2006 English cricket season|2006]] for a four-match [[Test cricket|Test]] series, a five-match [[One Day International]] series and a single [[Twenty20 International]]. After a drawn first Test, England won the next two matches before being awarded the final match in controversial circumstances; on the fourth day, Pakistan's players were penalised for [[ball tampering]] and refused to resume play after the tea interval, leading the umpires to award England the match and a 3\u20130 series victory. In 2008, the ICC controversially declared the result of the final Test as a draw, altering the scoreline to 2\u20130; however, after criticism, not least by the MCC, this was subsequently reversed in February 2009 and the result restored as an England victory.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\">{{cite news |title=Result U-turn for 2006 Oval Test |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7863464.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 February 2009 |accessdate=1 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n\n\n==Background==\n[[England cricket team|England]] had [[English cricket team in Pakistan in 2005\u201306|toured Pakistan]] the previous winter, with Pakistan winning the three-match Test series 2\u20130 and the five-match ODI series 3\u20132. As a result of the Test series, Pakistan rose two spots in the world Test rankings to be ranked second going into the return tour, and England dropped to third after the 12 July annual update of the [[ICC Test Championship]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Match\n! Venue\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | June\n|-\n| 27 || ODI v Scotland || [[The Grange, Edinburgh (cricket and sports club)|The Grange]]\n|- \n! colspan=\"3\" | July\n|-\n| 1\u20133 || Tour match || [[Grace Road]]\n|-\n| 6\u20139 || Tour match || [[St Lawrence Ground]]\n|-\n| 13\u201317 || 1st Test || [[Lord's]]\n|-\n| 20\u201323 || Tour match || [[County Cricket Ground, Northampton|County Ground, Northampton]]\n|-\n| 27\u201331 || 2nd Test || [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | August\n|-\n| 4\u20138 || 3rd Test || [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]]\n|-\n| 12 || Tour match || [[Denis Compton Oval]]\n|-\n| 13 || Tour match || [[Denis Compton Oval]]\n|-\n| 17\u201321 || 4th Test || [[The Oval]]\n|-\n| 28 || T20I || [[County Cricket Ground, Bristol|County Ground, Bristol]]\n|-\n| 30 || 1st ODI || [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]]\n|- \n! colspan=\"3\" | September\n|-\n| 2 || 2nd ODI || [[Lord's]]\n|-\n| 5 || 3rd ODI || [[The Rose Bowl, Hampshire|The Rose Bowl, Southampton]]\n|-\n| 8 || 4th ODI || [[Trent Bridge]]\n|-\n| 10 || 5th ODI || [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground|Edgbaston]]\n|}\n\n==Squads==\n{| style=\"width:100%\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"width:46%\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Pakistan<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/squad/249959.html Pakistan Test Squad], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref>\n|-\n! Name\n! style=\"width:20%\"| Style\n! Domestic team(s)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] [[captain (cricket)|c]] || RHB, [[Slow left arm|SLA]] || [[Multan cricket team|Multan]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Kamran Akmal]] [[wicketkeeper|wk]] || RHB || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Lahore Ravi cricket team|Lahore Ravi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[Lahore Ravi cricket team|Lahore Ravi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Danish Kaneria]] || RHB, [[Leg break|LB]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]], [[Karachi Urban cricket team|Karachi Urban]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Faisal Iqbal]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA]], [[Karachi Harbour cricket team|Karachi Harbour]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Iftikhar Anjum]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RM]] || [[Zarai Taraqiati Bank Limited|ZTBL]], [[Islamabad cricket team|Islamabad]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Imran Farhat]] || LHB, [[Leg break|LB]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]], [[Lahore Shalimar cricket team|Lahore Shalimar]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] || LHB, [[Fast bowling|RFM]] || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Sialkot cricket team|Sialkot]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Hafeez]] || RHB, [[Off break|OB]] || [[Sui Northern Gas Pipelines Limited|SNGPL]], [[Faisalabad cricket team|Faisalabad]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Sami]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RF]] || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Karachi Harbour cricket team|Karachi Harbour]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] || RHB || [[Water and Power Development Authority|WAPDA]], [[Lahore Ravi cricket team|Lahore Ravi]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Naved-ul-Hasan]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|RMF]] ||[[Sialkot cricket team|Sialkot]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Salman Butt]] || LHB, [[Off spin|OB]] || [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|NBP]], [[Lahore Shalimar cricket team|Lahore Shalimar]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Samiullah Khan Niazi]] || RHB, [[Fast bowling|LMF]] || [[Sui Northern Gas Pipelines Limited|SNGPL]], [[Faisalabad cricket team|Faisalabad]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Shahid Afridi]] || RHB, [[Leg break|LBG]] || [[Habib Bank Limited cricket team|HBL]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Shahid Nazir]] || RHB, [