eved 24 August 2006</ref>\n\nGough withdrew after the second ODI with a shin injury, and Onions was called up to replace him.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/england/5310512.stm Injured Gough replaced by Onions], from BBC, retrieved 4 September 2006</ref>\n|}\n|}\n\n==Tour matches==\n===First-class: Leicestershire v Pakistanis===\n{{Test match\n| date = 1\u20133 July 2006\n| team1 = [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 315/9[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (81 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Dinesh Mongia]] 129 (234)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Mohammad Sami]] 3/53 (17 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 304/5[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (85 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Imran Farhat]] 81 (132)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Nick Walker (cricketer)|Nick Walker]] 3/47 (24 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 191 (43 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Tom New]] 67 (108)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 4/32 (11 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 207/2 (40.2 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Shoaib Malik]] 110 (124)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Chris Liddle]] 2/27 (10 overs)\n| result = Pakistanis won by 8 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225259.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Grace Road]], [[Leicester]]\n| umpires = [[Neil Bainton]] (Eng) and [[John Holder (cricketer)|John Holder]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistanis won the toss and elected to field.\n| notes = [[Matthew Boyce]] (Leics) made his first-class debut.\n}}\n\n===First-class: Pakistanis v England A===\n{{Test match\n| date = 1\u20133 July 2006\n| team1 = [[England Lions cricket team|England A]] {{flagicon|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 595/9[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (173 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Chris Read]] 150[[Not out|*]]\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 4/158 (48 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 242 (73.1 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Faisal Iqbal]] 82 (150)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Jamie Dalrymple]] 4/61 (24 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 153/1[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (44.1 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Alastair Cook]] 80 (128)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Imran Farhat]] 1/46 (20 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 154/2 (50 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Salman Butt]] 50 (90)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = \n| result = Match drawn\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225260.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Grace Road]], [[Leicester]]\n| umpires = [[Daryl Hair]] (Aus) and [[Richard Illingworth]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistanis won the toss and elected to field.\n| notes = In Pakistan's second innings, both batsmen retired out.\n}}\n\n===First-class: Northamptonshire v Pakistanis===\n{{Test match\n|date = 20\u201322 July 2006\n| team1 = [[Northamptonshire County Cricket Club|Northamptonshire]]\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 269/3[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (62.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Stephen Peters]] 142 (195)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Samiullah Khan (cricketer)|Samiullah Khan]] 2/35 (8.3 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 250/9[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (64.5 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 202 (330)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[David Wigley]] 5/77 (22.5 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 140 (38.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Ben Phillips (cricketer)|Ben Phillips]] 39 (58)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Shahid Nazir]] 3/33 (7 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 160/3 (40.2 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Salman Butt]] 84 (120)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Bilal Shafayat]] 2/25 (7 overs)\n| result = Pakistanis won by 7 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225261.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Wantage Road]], [[Northampton]]\n| umpires = [[Nick Cook (cricketer)|Nick Cook]] (Eng) and [[Neil Mallender]] (Eng)\n| toss = Northamptonshire won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\n\n===One-day: Pakistanis vs West Indies A===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 12 August 2013\n| time = 10:45\n| team1 = [[West Indies A cricket team|West Indies A]] {{flagicon|WIN}}\n| score1 = 214/4 (40 overs)\n| score2 = 123/3 (22 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| runs1 = [[Lendl Simmons]] 108[[not out|*]] (122)\n| wickets1 = [[Samiullah Khan (cricketer)|Samiullah Khan]] 3/30 (6 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Imran Farhat]] 62[[not out|*]] (43)\n| wickets2 = [[Richard Kelly (cricketer, born 1984)|Richard Kelly]] 2/27 (5 overs)\n| result = No result\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/engine/match/225262.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Denis Compton Oval]], [[Shenley, Hertfordshire|Shenley]]\n| umpires = [[Trevor Jesty]] (Eng) and [[Richard Kettleborough]] (Eng)\n| motm = \n| toss = Pakistanis won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = Rain meant the match was reduced to 40 overs a side. Further rain ended the Pakistanis' innings after 22 overs.\n| notes = \n}}\n\n===List A: Pakistanis vs West Indies A===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 13 August 2013\n| time = 10:45\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK|name=Pakistanis}}\n| score1 = \n| score2 =\n| team2 = {{flagicon|WIN}} [[West Indies A cricket team|West Indies A]] \n| result = Match abandoned without a ball bowled\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/255928.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Denis Compton Oval]], [[Shenley, Hertfordshire|Shenley]]\n| umpires = [[Trevor Jesty]] (Eng) and [[Richard Kettleborough]] (Eng)\n| toss = No toss.\n| rain = No play was possible due to a waterlogged pitch.\n}}\n\n==Test series==\n===1st Test===\n{{Test match\n|date = 13\u201317 July 2006\n|team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 528/9[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (158.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Paul Collingwood]] 186 (327)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 3/119 (52 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 445 (119.3 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 202 (330)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Steve Harmison]] 4/94 (29.3 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 296/8[[declaration and forfeiture|d]] (84.5 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Andrew Strauss]] 128 (214)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Danish Kaneria]] 3/77 (30 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 214/4 (73 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] 56 (111)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Monty Panesar]] 2/60 (27 overs)\n| result = Match drawn\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225255.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Lord's]], London\n| umpires = [[Simon Taufel]] (Aus) and [[Steve Bucknor]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (Pak)\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\nEngland made an opening stand 60 runs before losing their first two wickets in quick succession, as [[Marcus Trescothick]] fell, followed an over later by captain [[Andrew Strauss]]. [[Kevin Pietersen]] was the next man out, adding just 28 runs for the third wicket, but [[Alastair Cook]] and [[Paul Collingwood]] both reached centuries on the way to a fourth-wicket partnership of 233 runs before Cook was out for 105. Collingwood top-scored in the innings with 186, and [[Ian Bell]] also managed an unbeaten 100 before England immediately declared on 528/9 with half a session left in the second day's play.\n\n[[Steve Harmison]] took two wickets in three balls before the close of play, helping England reduce Pakistan to 68/4 early on the third day; however, [[Mohammad Yousuf]] and captain [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] added 173 runs for the fifth wicket, and [[Kamran Akmal]] also made a half-century, reaching 58 before he was caught behind off the bowling of [[Kevin Pietersen]]. Despite partners falling around him, [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer)|Mohammad Yousuf]] managed to bat on to a double-century before he was caught behind off Harmison to close the innings \u2013 Harmison finished with figures of 4/94.\n\nEngland began the process of building on their 83-run lead early on the fourth day, but Strauss' 128 was the only notable score as they amassed 296 runs before declaring early on the final day, giving Pakistan a target of 380 to chase in 73 overs. [[Salman Butt]] fell to the first ball of the innings from Hoggard, followed by [[Imran Farhat]] to leave the tourists at 33/2; however, scores of 48 from [[Faisal Iqbal]] and Mohammad Yousuf got them to 141/4, before Inzamam-ul-Haq and [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] batted out the last session for 73 to secure a draw.\n\n===2nd Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 27\u201329 July 2006\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK}}\n| team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 119 (38.4 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Younis Khan]] 44 (62)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Steve Harmison]] 6/19 (13 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 461/9[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (133 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Alastair Cook]] 127 (260)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Umar Gul]] 3/96 (28 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 222 (67.1 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Younis Khan]] 62 (119)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Steve Harmison]] 5/57 (18.1 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = \n| runs-team2-inns2 = \n| wickets-team2-inns2 = \n| result = England won by an innings and 120 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225256.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]], Manchester\n| umpires = [[Simon Taufel]] (Aus) and [[Steve Bucknor]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Steve Harmison]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\nWith [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]]'s run of half-centuries against England finally stopped, as he was caught by [[Kevin Pietersen]] off [[Steve Harmison]]'s bowling for a duck, England recorded an innings victory over Pakistan to take a 1\u20130 lead into the third Test. In the first innings, Pakistan lost the last eight wickets for 29 to post 119 with no batsmen making a half-century; England surpassed that score for the loss of two wickets, and with [[Alastair Cook]] and [[Ian Bell]] both making hundreds (127 and 106* respectively), England could eventually declare near the end of day two having made 461. It took England 63 overs to clean up, with Harmison and [[Monty Panesar]] sharing the ten wickets evenly (the only wicket takers in both innings) with the help of wicket keeper [[Geraint Jones]], who caught five despite his fractured finger. Panesar took his second five-wicket-haul in three months, and was praised by opposition coach [[Bob Woolmer]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/england/5229112.stm Panesar tipped for greatness], from BBC, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref>\n\n===3rd Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 4\u20138 August 2006\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 515 (123 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Kevin Pietersen]] 135 (169)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Umar Gul]] 5/123 (29 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 538 (141.4 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 192 (261)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Monty Panesar]] 3/127 (47.4 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 345 (88.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Andrew Strauss]] 116 (171)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Shahid Nazir]] 3/32 (14 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 155 (47.5 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Younis Khan]] 41 (83)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Sajid Mahmood]] 4/22 (8 overs)\n| result = England won by 167 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225257.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]], Leeds\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Darrell Hair]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\nAfter their innings defeat in the second test, Pakistan dropped [[Shahid Afridi]] and [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]], and had to swap [[Imran Farhat]] out due to injury. They brought in [[Salman Butt]] and [[Taufeeq Umar]] to open the innings, plus the bowling of [[Shahid Nazir]]. England only made one change, which was to swap the struggling wicketkeeper [[Geraint Jones]] for [[Chris Read]]. The wicketkeeper position had been the subject of much debate. Read was perceived as the better keeper, although Jones\u2019 batting skills were considered to be superior. However, Jones had not scored a significant innings for some time and Read was given an opportunity to impress for the first time since the West Indies tour of 2004.\n\nThe first day of the test prompted some interesting incidents as England won the toss and batted first. In the morning, there were three rogue decisions from the umpires (who had been testing the use of earpieces to communicate with off-field officials); in the afternoon Kevin Pietersen left the field in bizarre circumstances, and Pakistan responded with 11 overs of very mediocre bowling, using their opening batsmen to bowl during the period before the second new ball was due.\n\nIn amongst all this, Pietersen scored his 5th test century, and helped propel England to 347/6 by the end of the day. England continued on day 2, with [[Ian Bell]] posting his third consecutive test century, and the lower order added useful runs before England were bowled out for 515.\n\nPakistan's openers once again struggled, and they fell quickly to leave the tourists on 36/2. However, the experienced combination of [[Younis Khan]] and [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] then combined to produce the largest partnership for Pakistan against England of 363 for the third wicket. They batted well into the afternoon session of the third day, before Yousuf gloved [[Stephen Harmison]] through to the keeper having scored 192.\n\nPakistan then lost some of their advantage in a bizarre passage of play leading up to the tea interval. Younis was run out on 173, [[Faisal Iqbal]] fell lbw to his first delivery faced (giving [[Paul Collingwood]] his first test wicket), and [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] lost his wicket in a comical way, overbalancing while attempting to sweep a [[Monty Panesar]] delivery and falling onto his stumps.\n\nThe lower order batsmen tried to accelerate the scoring, but lost regular wickets in the process, and Pakistan were finally bowled out for 538.\n\nEngland's second innings started well, with the openers putting on 158 for the first wicket. [[Andrew Strauss]] went on to score 116, and [[Chris Read]] scored 55 down the order, but the other wickets fell quite regularly as England attempted to set up a position where they could push for a win on the final day. Pakistan's bowling attack shared the wickets between them, and eventually bowled England out for 345. Pakistan needed 323 runs on the final day to win.\n\nEngland's bowlers performed well on the final day, and took 5 wickets in the first session ensuring the 323 run target was well out of Pakistan's reach. The run out of [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] for a single figure score was a key moment in the innings \u2013 in fact, Pakistan lost 3 of their top order batsmen to run outs during the game. [[Sajid Mahmood]] struck twice in an over shortly before lunch to remove [[Faisal Iqbal]] and [[Kamran Akmal]], and would go on to record test best figures of 4/22.\n\n[[Monty Panesar]] also demonstrated his promising talent, taking 3 wickets in the second innings to follow up on 3 wickets in the first, on a pitch not typically associated with assisting spinners. His dismissal of [[Younis Khan]] during the afternoon session was spectacular, with a wonderfully flighted delivery that just clipped the bail of the off stump.\n\nFrom this point, it was a matter of time before England took the honours.\n\nAs a result of a rib injury obtained during the course of the Test (and determined to be an ''internal'' injury rather than an ''external'' one<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5253966.stm | work=BBC News | title=Rib injury keeps Inzamam waiting | date=7 August 2006}}</ref>) the Pakistan Captain, [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]], was unable to bat for 4h20m in the Pakistan 2nd innings, or until the fall of the 5th wicket (whichever came first). As England took five wickets in the first session of the last day, he was able to come in at number 7 in the order. His wicket was eventually the last to fall, being stumped off the bowling of [[Monty Panesar]], and Pakistan were all out for 155.\n\nEngland won the match by 167 runs, and took an unassailable 2\u20130 lead in the series, with one left to play.\n\n===4th Test===\n{{main|2006 ball-tampering controversy}}\n{{Test match\n| date = 17\u201320 August 2006\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 173 (53.2 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Alastair Cook]] 40 (69)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Umar Gul]] 4/46 (15.2 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 504 (129.5 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 128 (236)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Monty Panesar|MS Panesar]] 4/125 (30.5 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 298/4 (72 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Kevin Pietersen]] 96 (114)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Shahid Nazir]] 1/26 (8 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 =\n| runs-team2-inns2 =\n| wickets-team2-inns2 =\n| result = England awarded the match<br />(opposition refused to play)\n| venue = [[The Oval]], London\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Darrell Hair]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)<br />Players of the Series: [[Andrew Strauss]] (Eng) and [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (Pak)\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225258.html Scorecard]\n| notes = Match abandoned on day 4 because Pakistan refused to resume play after tea.\n| rain = \n}}\nPakistan made three changes to their side for the final test. The uncertainty of the opening pair continued, with [[Salman Butt]] and [[Taufeeq Umar]] being dropped in favour of [[Imran Farhat]] and [[Mohammad Hafeez]]. The tourists' bowling ranks were boosted by the return of [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]], for whom [[Mohammad Sami]] made way.\n\nPakistan won the toss and chose to field in cloudy conditions. This proved to be a good decision, as Pakistan's seamers [[Umar Gul]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] took eight wickets between them on the way to bowling England out for 173. Asif in particular caused problems for England's batsmen, and left people wondering what the outcome of the series would have been had he not been injured for the earlier tests.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nLate on day 1, Pakistan began their reply confidently, and their fourth opening partnership combination of the series proved to be the most successful one. Hafeez hit some good shots before retiring hurt with a knee problem. He would return to complete his innings and score 95, while Farhat scored 91. England's poor first day was complete when they dropped [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] twice before he reached double figures. He went on to score 128, his third century of the series.\n\nPakistan continued their dominance of the match on day 2, with the close of play score at 336/3, a lead of 163. On day 3, England finally managed to start taking wickets in between frequent rain and bad light interruptions, but they were not able to curtail Pakistan's scoring. [[Faisal Iqbal]] ended on 58 not out, his first contribution in the series. Pakistan were finally bowled out for 504, a lead of 331.\n\n[[Marcus Trescothick]] was dismissed early in England's second innings, in what would be his last test match appearance for England to date. [[Andrew Strauss]] and [[Alastair Cook]] then progressed the score to 78/1 at the close of play.\n\nThe (what would prove to be eventful) fourth day began with Strauss and Cook continuing on the improved batting performance before Strauss fell lbw to [[Danish Kaneria]] with the score on 115. [[Kevin Pietersen]] came in and played an aggressive innings, hitting 96 from 114 deliveries, and only falling when he chased a wide delivery in an attempt to bring up his century.\n\nThe dismissal of Cook for 83 off the bowling of [[Umar Gul]], with a delivery of reverse swing, resulted in umpires [[Darrell Hair]] and [[Billy Doctrove]] calling a halt to play so a set of used balls could be brought out to the middle. England were awarded 5 penalty runs and this event was the catalyst for the subsequent refusal to continue the match after tea by the Pakistan team. Based on the laws of cricket, the umpires declared Pakistan to have forfeited the game and [[Result_(cricket)#Awarded|awarded]] England the win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5268886.stm |title=Lengthy talks fail to save Test |publisher=BBC |date=20 August 2006 |accessdate=20 August 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/5269906.stm |title=Inzamam charged in cheating row |publisher=BBC |date=21 August 2006 |accessdate=21 August 2006 }}</ref> The ICC later changed the result of the match to a draw,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/359329.html |title=ICC changes Oval forfeiture to draw |publisher=ESPN Sports Media |date=3 July 2008 |accessdate=21 September 2011 }}</ref> and then later reversed this decision on 1 February 2009.<ref name=\"award2009\">{{cite news|title=Cricket: England awarded Oval Test 'win' against Pakistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/feb/01/england-pakistan-oval|accessdate=8 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n==T20 series==\n===Only T20I===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 28 August 2006\n| time = 15:00\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 144/7 (20 overs)\n| score2 = 148/5 (17.5 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Marcus Trescothick]] 53 (36)\n| wickets1 = [[Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzaq]] 3/30 (4 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] 46 (40)\n| wickets2 = [[Stuart Broad]] 2/35 (4 overs)\n| result = Pakistan won by 5 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225263.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Nevil Road]], [[Bristol]]\n| umpires = [[Peter Hartley (cricketer)|Peter Hartley]] and [[Nigel Llong]]\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to bat.\n| rain = [[Ian Bell]], [[Stuart Broad]] and [[Michael Yardy]] (all Eng) made their T20I debuts.\n| notes = This was Pakistan's first T20I match.\n}}\n\nPakistan won the match by five wickets. After bowling out four of England's upper order batsmen for fewer than 20 runs between them, Pakistan secured a comfortable win aided by Shahid Afridi who struck 28 off just 10 balls (22 of these in a single over).\n\n==England ODI series==\n===1st ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 30 August 2006\n| time = 14:30\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 202 (49.2 overs)\n| score2 = 46/1 (7 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Ian Bell]] 88 (117)\n| wickets1 = [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] 3/28 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] 18[[Not out|*]] (23)\n| wickets2 = [[Stuart Broad]] 1/14 (3 overs)\n| result = No result\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225245.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]], [[Cardiff]]\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Ian Gould]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = Pakistan innings reduced to 32 overs due to rain.\n}}\n\n===2nd ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 2 September 2006\n| time = 10:15\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 166 (39.1 overs)\n| score2 = 169/3 (36.4 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Rikki Clarke]] 39 (47)\n| wickets1 = [[Shoaib Akhtar]] 4/28 (8 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Younis Khan]] 55 (89)\n| wickets2 = [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] 2/11 (8 overs)\n| result = Pakistan won by 7 wickets ([[Duckworth\u2013Lewis method|D/L]])\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225246.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Lord's]], [[London]]\n| umpires = [[Mark Benson]] and [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Shoaib Akhtar]] (Pak)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = Late start due to rain reduced both innings to 46 overs; further rain reduced Pakistan innings to 40 overs.\n}}\n\n===3rd ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 5 September 2006\n| time = 14:30\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 271/9 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 274/8 (48.5 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Jamie Dalrymple]] 62 (78)\n| wickets1 = [[Naved-ul-Hasan]] 4/57 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Younis Khan]] 101 (109)\n| wickets2 = [[Stuart Broad]] 3/57 (10 over)\n| result = Pakistan won by 2 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225247.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]], [[Southampton]]\n| umpires = [[Billy Doctrove]] (WI) and [[Nigel Llong]]\n| motm = [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n}}\nShoaib Akhtar was in the spotlight after television cameras caught him working on the ball. The pictures appeared to show Akhtar flicking his thumb at the ball. However, [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] referee [[Mike Procter]] analysed the TV footage and decided there was no case to answer on behalf of the Pakistani team.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5312576.stm Match report] accessed 6 September 2006</ref>\n\n===4th ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 8 September 2006\n| time = 14:30\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK}}\n| score1 = 235/8 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 237/2 (46.2 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n| runs1 = [[Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzaq]] 75[[Not out|*]] (72)\n| wickets1 = [[Michael Yardy]] 3/24 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Ian Bell]] 86[[Not out|*]] (111)\n| wickets2 = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] 1/21 (4.2 overs)\n| result = England won by 8 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225248.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Trent Bridge]], [[Nottingham]]\n| umpires = [[Mark Benson]] and [[Daryl Harper]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Ian Bell]] (Eng)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to bat.\n| notes = [[Michael Yardy]] (Eng) made his ODI debut.\n}}\n\n===5th ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 10 September 2006\n| time = 10:15\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|PAK}}\n| score1 = 154/9 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 155/7 (31 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|ENG}}\n| runs1 = [[Younis Khan]] 47 (80)\n| wickets1 = [[Jamie Dalrymple]] 2/13 (6 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Andrew Strauss]] 35 (41)\n| wickets2 = [[Shahid Afridi]] 2/14 (5 overs)\n| result = England won by 3 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/225249.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Edgebaston]], [[Birmingham]]\n| umpires = [[Ian Gould]] (Eng) and [[Daryl Harper]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Sajid Mahmood]] (Eng)<br>'''Man of the Series''': [[Younis Khan]] (Pak)\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to field.\n}}\n\n==Scotland ODI series==\n===Only ODI===\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 27 June 2006\n| time = 10:45\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|SCO}}\n| score1 = 203/8 (50 overs)\n| score2 = 205/5 (43.5 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|PAK}}\n| runs1 = [[Ryan Watson (cricketer)|Ryan Watson]] 80 (85)\n| wickets1 = [[Shoaib Malik]] 3/35 (10 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] 83[[Not out|*]] (113)\n| wickets2 = [[Paul Hoffmann (cricketer)|Paul Hoffmann]] 3/22 (10 overs)\n| result = Pakistan won by 5 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvpak/engine/match/240777.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Grange Cricket Club Ground]], [[Edinburgh]]\n| umpires = [[Daryl Hair]] (Aus) and [[Subhash Modi]] (Ken)\n| motm = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (Pak)\n| toss = Pakistan won the toss and elected to field.\n| notes = [[Paul Hoffmann (cricketer)|Paul Hoffmann]], [[Dougie Lockhart]], [[Ross Lyons]], [[Neil McCallum (cricketer)|Neil McCallum]], [[Neil MacRae]], [[Dewald Nel]], [[Colin Smith (Scottish cricketer)|Colin Smith]] and [[Ryan Watson (cricketer)|Ryan Watson]] (all Sco) made their ODI debuts.\n}}\nPakistan won the match by five wickets, after Scotland lost four wickets in the first eight overs and then four more in the remaining 42. [[Ryan Watson (cricketer)|Ryan Watson]] and [[Neil McCallum (cricketer)|Neil McCallum]] put on 116 for the fifth wicket, an ODI record partnership for [[Scotland national cricket team|Scotland]], who played their first ODI for seven years.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/SCOT/BATTING/ODI_PARTNERSHIP_RECORDS_SCOT.html ODI Partnership Records for Scotland], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref> Their innings also doubled the number of ODI fifties scored for Scotland.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/SCOT/BATTING/ODI_BAT_HIGH_INNS_SCORES_SCOT.html ODI Career Highest Individual Scores], from Cricinfo, retrieved 31 July 2006</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* ''Playfair Cricket Annual''\n* ''Wisden Cricketers Almanack 2007''\n\n==External sources==\n[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Seasons/Tours_2006.html CricketArchive]\n\n{{International cricket in 2006}}\n{{International cricket tours of Pakistan}}\n{{International cricket tours of England}}\n\n[[Category:Pakistani cricket tours of England|2006]]\n[[Category:2006 in English cricket]]\n[[Category:International cricket competitions in 2006]]\n[[Category:Cricket controversies]]\n[[Category:2006 in Pakistani cricket]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMohammad Yousuf(link changed toMohammad Yousuf (cricketer)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistani_cricket_team_in_England_in_2006"}
{"title_page": "Combined Arms Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation", "text_new": "{{Infobox University\n|name            = Combined Military Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation\n|native_name     = ''\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438''\n|logo=File:Mo narznaki90 1.png\n|image_name      = File:OVA RF.JPG\n|image_size      = 150px\n|caption         = The main entrance to the academy building\n|anniversaries= \n|established     = 1998\n|type            = [[Military academy]]\n|city            = [[Moscow]]\n|country         = [[Russia]]\n|rector          = Lieutenant General Aleksander Romanchuk\n}}\nThe '''Combined Arms Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation''' is a [[military academy]] in [[Moscow]] which prepares commissioned officers for the [[Russian Armed Forces]]. The full name reads: ''The Combined Academies [[Order of Lenin]] [[Order of the October Revolution]] [[Order of the Red Banner|Red Bannered]] [[Order of Suvorov]] of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation-[[Military Educational and Scientific Center]] of the Russian Ground Forces'' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \"\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u041e\u043a\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f, \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0443\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\"}}). There are 30 departments within the academy which are stationed in two main buildings in [[Khamovniki District|Khamovniki]] and [[Lefortovo District]]s of Moscow. It has a source of historical origin and functionally duplicates the [[General Staff Academy (Russia)]]. Since 2019, the current Commandant of the Combined Military Academy is [[Lieutenant General]] Aleksander Romanchuk.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Frunze Military Academy|Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy}}\nThe predecessors of the Academy were the [[Frunze Military Academy]] and the [[Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy]] and the Shaposhnikov Higher Officer Courses \u201cShot\u201d. The CAA was formed in 1998 on the base of both the Frunze Military Academy and the Armored Forces Academy. Since 2006, on the basis of decree  No. 473 of the [[Government of Russia]], the Military Institute of the Engineering Troops was included as a structural unit in the reorganization of the V. V. Kuybyshev Military Engineering Academy. In December 2008, its name was expanded to reflect its status as an institution. The reorganization was carried out by joining the academy with state educational institutions of higher professional education:\n\n*[[Far Eastern Higher Combined Arms Command School]]\n*Kazan Higher Military Command School\n*[[Moscow Higher Military Command School]]\n*Novosibirsk Higher Military Command School\n*Yekaterinburg Higher Artillery Command School\n*[[Ryazan Higher Airborne Command School]]\n*Omsk Tank Engineering Institute\n*Chelyabinsk Higher Military Automobile Command Engineering School\n*Penza Artillery Engineering Institute\n*Tula Artillery Engineering Institute\n*Military Institute for Advanced Studies of Specialists of Mobilization Bodies of the Armed Forces ([[Saratov]])\n\nOn 5 June 2007, in accordance with the a decree of the President [[Vladimir Putin]], a combat banner was awarded. The Academy is subordinate to the [[Commander-in-Chief of the Russian Ground Forces]].<ref>[http://vagsh.mil.ru/edumap \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439 - \u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u0442\u0430\u0431\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438<!-- \u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0431\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c -->]</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe Combined Arms Academy carries out the following activities: training for commandimg officers and military engineers with higher professional education and conducting fundamental and applied scientific research aimed at solving the problems of strengthening the country's defense capability and improving the professional education of military personnel. Organizationally, academy consists of a command with a management apparatus, a military institute for the engineering troops, 1 branch, faculties, departments, research groups and laboratories, academic courses, doctoral studies, postgraduate studies, units and educational process support services. In all full-time faculties, officers have been trained for 2 years to fill positions in the brigade level.\n\n===Foreign cadets===\nOfficers and cadets of foreign armies are trained at special faculties. The term of their training is the same as that of Russian students and cadets, but preliminary. During the year, some of them study the [[Russian language]] in a preparatory course. The training of foreign military personnel is carried out in Russian practically according to the same plans and programs as Russian military personnel with restrictions in accordance with the specific bilateral and multilateral agreements that are concluded.\n\n===Band===\nBand of the Combined Arms Academy was formed in 1998 from Frunze Military Academy Band and the Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy Band. This gives the band an over 85-year history. By order of the Chairman of the Revolutionary Military Council on 19 December 1931, a military band at the Frunze Military Academy was created. The first artistic director of the band was Colonel V. Gurfinkel. During the [[Great Patriotic War]], many musicians of the band as part of the front-line brigades went to the front with concerts for fighters and commanders of the [[Red Army]]. It has performed at the largest concert venues in the capital: including the [[Kremlin Palace of Congresses]], the [[House of the Unions]], and the Tchaikovsky Concert Hall. On the All-Union Radio, the academy band recorded seven discs and over one hundred and twenty works of Soviet and foreign composers. In 1972, the team traveled to [[Belgium]] to participate in the celebration of the Independence Day and in 1990 gave a concert on the [[Champs Elysees]] in [[Paris]].<ref>https://spasstower.ru/participants/orkestr-obshchevoyskovoy-akademii-vooruzhennykh-sil/</ref><ref>https://ria.ru/amp/20190704/1556219964.html</ref>\n\n===Decorations===\n*[[File:Order of Lenin ribbon bar.png|30px]] [[Order of Lenin]] \n*[[File:Order october revolution rib.png|30px]] [[Order of the October Revolution]]\n*[[File:Order of Red Banner ribbon bar.png|30px]] [[Order of Red Banner]]\n*[[File:Order of Suvorov 106x30.png|30px]][[Order of Suvorov]]\n\n==Heads==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin at award ceremonies (2018-12-18) 1.jpg|thumb|President Putin awarding the academy in 2018.]]\n*[[Colonel General]] Leonid Zolotov (August 1998 - September 2002)\n*Colonel General Vladimir Popov (September 2002 - December 2009)\n*[[Major General]] Alexey Kim (December 2009 - January 2010)\n*Lieutenant General Viktor Polyakov (January 2010 - July 2014)\n*Lieutenant General Oleg Makarevich (July 2014 - September 2017)\n*Lieutenant General Alexander Lapin (September - November 2017)\n*Lieutenant General Sergey Yudin (November 2017 - April 2018) (''Interim'')\n*Lieutenant General Alexey Avdeev (April 2018 - 2019)\n*[[Lieutenant General]] Aleksander Romanchuk (Since 2019)\n\n==Alumni==\n*[[Sulim Yamadayev]]\n*[[Oleg Kozlov]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Soviet military academies]]\n*[[Combined Arms Training Centre (Australia)]]\n*[[United States Army Combined Arms Center]]\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070526054824/http://www.mil.ru/848/1045/1272/21010/21014/22541/index.shtml\n\n{{coord|55|44|16|N|37|34|40|E|region:RU-MOW_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Military academies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Universities in Moscow]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations awarded the Order of the Red Banner]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox University\n|name            = Combined Military Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation\n|native_name     = ''\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438''\n|logo=File:Mo narznaki90 1.png\n|image_name      = File:OVA RF.JPG\n|image_size      = 150px\n|caption         = The main entrance to the academy building\n|anniversaries= \n|established     = 1998\n|type            = [[Military academy]]\n|city            = [[Moscow]]\n|country         = [[Russia]]\n|rector          = Lieutenant General Aleksander Romanchuk\n}}\nThe '''Combined Arms Academy of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation''' is a [[military academy]] in [[Moscow]] which prepares commissioned officers for the [[Russian Armed Forces]]. The full name reads: ''The Combined Academies [[Order of Lenin]] [[Order of the October Revolution]] [[Order of the Red Banner|Red Bannered]] [[Order of Suvorov]] of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation-[[Military Educational and Scientific Center]] of the Russian Ground Forces'' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0431\u043d\u043e-\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0421\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \"\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u041e\u043a\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f, \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0443\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\"}}). There are 30 departments within the academy which are stationed in two main buildings in [[Khamovniki District|Khamovniki]] and [[Lefortovo District]]s of Moscow. It has a source of historical origin and functionally duplicates the [[General Staff Academy (Russia)]]. Since 2019, the current Commandant of the Combined Military Academy is [[Lieutenant General]] Aleksander Romanchuk.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Frunze Military Academy|Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy}}\nThe predecessors of the Academy were the the [[Frunze Military Academy]] and the [[Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy]] and the Shaposhnikov Higher Officer Courses \u201cShot\u201d. The CAA was formed in 1998 on the base of both the Frunze Military Academy and the Armored Forces Academy. Since 2006, on the basis of decree  No. 473 of the [[Government of Russia]], the Military Institute of the Engineering Troops was included as a structural unit in the reorganization of the V. V. Kuybyshev Military Engineering Academy. In December 2008, its name was expanded to reflect its status as an institution. The reorganization was carried out by joining the academy with state educational institutions of higher professional education:\n\n*[[Far Eastern Higher Combined Arms Command School]]\n*Kazan Higher Military Command School\n*[[Moscow Higher Military Command School]]\n*Novosibirsk Higher Military Command School\n*Yekaterinburg Higher Artillery Command School\n*[[Ryazan Higher Airborne Command School]]\n*Omsk Tank Engineering Institute\n*Chelyabinsk Higher Military Automobile Command Engineering School\n*Penza Artillery Engineering Institute\n*Tula Artillery Engineering Institute\n*Military Institute for Advanced Studies of Specialists of Mobilization Bodies of the Armed Forces ([[Saratov]])\n\nOn 5 June 2007, in accordance with the a decree of the President [[Vladimir Putin]], a combat banner was awarded. The Academy is subordinate to the [[Commander-in-Chief of the Russian Ground Forces]].<ref>[http://vagsh.mil.ru/edumap \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439 - \u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u0442\u0430\u0431\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438<!-- \u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0431\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c -->]</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe Combined Arms Academy carries out the following activities: training for commandimg officers and military engineers with higher professional education and conducting fundamental and applied scientific research aimed at solving the problems of strengthening the country's defense capability and improving the professional education of military personnel. Organizationally, academy consists of a command with a management apparatus, a military institute for the engineering troops, 1 branch, faculties, departments, research groups and laboratories, academic courses, doctoral studies, postgraduate studies, units and educational process support services. In all full-time faculties, officers have been trained for 2 years to fill positions in the brigade level.\n\n===Foreign cadets===\nOfficers and cadets of foreign armies are trained at special faculties. The term of their training is the same as that of Russian students and cadets, but preliminary. During the year, some of them study the [[Russian language]] in a preparatory course. The training of foreign military personnel is carried out in Russian practically according to the same plans and programs as Russian military personnel with restrictions in accordance with the specific bilateral and multilateral agreements that are concluded.\n\n===Band===\nBand of the Combined Arms Academy was formed in 1998 from Frunze Military Academy Band and the Malinovsky Military Armored Forces Academy Band. This gives the band an over 85-year history. By order of the Chairman of the Revolutionary Military Council on 19 December 1931, a military band at the Frunze Military Academy was created. The first artistic director of the band was Colonel V. Gurfinkel. During the [[Great Patriotic War]], many musicians of the band as part of the front-line brigades went to the front with concerts for fighters and commanders of the [[Red Army]]. It has performed at the largest concert venues in the capital: including the [[Kremlin Palace of Congresses]], the [[House of the Unions]], and the Tchaikovsky Concert Hall. On the All-Union Radio, the academy band recorded seven discs and over one hundred and twenty works of Soviet and foreign composers. In 1972, the team traveled to [[Belgium]] to participate in the celebration of the Independence Day and in 1990 gave a concert on the [[Champs Elysees]] in [[Paris]].<ref>https://spasstower.ru/participants/orkestr-obshchevoyskovoy-akademii-vooruzhennykh-sil/</ref><ref>https://ria.ru/amp/20190704/1556219964.html</ref>\n\n===Decorations===\n*[[File:Order of Lenin ribbon bar.png|30px]] [[Order of Lenin]] \n*[[File:Order october revolution rib.png|30px]] [[Order of the October Revolution]]\n*[[File:Order of Red Banner ribbon bar.png|30px]] [[Order of Red Banner]]\n*[[File:Order of Suvorov 106x30.png|30px]][[Order of Suvorov]]\n\n==Heads==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin at award ceremonies (2018-12-18) 1.jpg|thumb|President Putin awarding the academy in 2018.]]\n*[[Colonel General]] Leonid Zolotov (August 1998 - September 2002)\n*Colonel General Vladimir Popov (September 2002 - December 2009)\n*[[Major General]] Alexey Kim (December 2009 - January 2010)\n*Lieutenant General Viktor Polyakov (January 2010 - July 2014)\n*Lieutenant General Oleg Makarevich (July 2014 - September 2017)\n*Lieutenant General Alexander Lapin (September - November 2017)\n*Lieutenant General Sergey Yudin (November 2017 - April 2018) (''Interim'')\n*Lieutenant General Alexey Avdeev (April 2018 - 2019)\n*[[Lieutenant General]] Aleksander Romanchuk (Since 2019)\n\n==Alumni==\n*[[Sulim Yamadayev]]\n*[[Oleg Kozlov]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Soviet military academies]]\n*[[Combined Arms Training Centre (Australia)]]\n*[[United States Army Combined Arms Center]]\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070526054824/http://www.mil.ru/848/1045/1272/21010/21014/22541/index.shtml\n\n{{coord|55|44|16|N|37|34|40|E|region:RU-MOW_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Military academies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Universities in Moscow]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations awarded the Order of the Red Banner]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combined_Arms_Academy_of_the_Armed_Forces_of_the_Russian_Federation"}
{"title_page": "William Edmondson", "text_new": "'''William Edmondson''' (c.1874\u20131951) was the first [[African-American]] [[folk art]] [[sculptor]] to be given a [[one-person show]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in [[New York City]] (1937).\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Edmondson\n| image              = File:William Edmonson.jpg\n| caption            = William Edmondson sculpting in his backyard\n| birth_date         = December, 1874\n| birth_place        = Davidson County, Nashville, Tennessee\n| death_date         = February 7th, 1951\n| death_place        = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| othername          = \n| birthname          = William M. Edmondson\n| occupation         = Sculptor\n}}\n\n==Biography==\nWilliam Edmondson was born sometime in December 1874 on the Compton Plantation in [[Davidson County, Tennessee]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Thompson|first=Robert Farris|title=The Art of William Edmondson|last2=Lovett|first2=Bobby L.|last3=Freeman|first3=Rusty|last4=McWillie|first4=Judith|date=January 1, 1999|publisher=Cheekwood Museum of Art|year=1999|isbn=1578061814|location=Cheekwood Museum of Art|pages=3-14, 15-32, 33-44, 45-60|oclc=41932532}}</ref> He did not know the date of his birth because of a fire that destroyed the family Bible.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book |last1=Edmondson |first1=William |last2=Thompson |first2=Robert Farris |last3=Freeman |first3=Rusty |title=The Art of William Edmondson |date=1999 |publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi |isbn=9781578061815 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCOLisQ4eCkC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17 |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=10 things to know about William Edmondson |url=https://www.christies.com/features/William-Edmondson-10-things-to-know-8027-1.aspx |website=Christie's |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Edmondson was one of six children born to Orange and Jane Edmondson who had been and previously enslaved before they worked as sharecroppers. Due to privilege regarding race and color, mulattoes on the plantation were given more respectable jobs where as the Edmonson's  mainly worked in the corn fields and handled livestock. The Edmondson family worked on the plantation and earned a mere 12 dollars a month. During these times in the corn fields he would see \"angels in the clouds\" and believe it was God talking to him. <ref name=\":1\" />  Edmondson had little or no formal education. \n\n\nWhen his father died in late 1889,16 year-old Edmondson refused to continue to tirelessly work on the plantation and left to Nashville for work.<ref name=\":1\" /> He got a good job working at the expansive new [[Nashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis Railroad]] shops. After an injury sustained at the Railway shops in 1907, Edmondson took a job as a custodian at the Nashville Women's Hospital, where he worked until the hospital closed in 1931<ref name=\":2\" />. During this time Edmondson family officially resided in Nashville as his mother, Jane, was the last to leave the Compton Plantation. By age 39, his wages at Women's Hospital allowed him to buy a modest home and spacious lot in Edgehill, a segregated neighborhood in Nashville's Vanderbilt-Belmont area<ref name=\":1\" />.  Edmondson never married and he shared the home with his mother and sister, as well as, occasionally, other siblings, nieces, and nephews. With Jane's passing in 1922, Edmonson's sister, Sarah, soon became the woman of the house. It was said she would often hold family barbecues that consisted of laughter and storytelling.<ref name=\":1\" />  When the hospital closed in 1931, Edmondson picked up work at various part-time jobs and in his leisure, he could be found in his backyard sculpting and selling his vegetables.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\nIn 1948 Edmondson stopped sculpting. On February 7th, 1951 at age seventy-six, he passed quietly in his home in Nashville, Tennessee, where illness had confined him to bed for several months. As he was the last of his siblings to pass, his five nieces and seven nephews carried out his funeral service which was held the next day<ref name=\":1\" />. William Edmondson was buried in Mount Ararat Cemetery, now [[Greenwood Cemetery (Nashville, Tennessee)]], Nashville's oldest black cemetery. Today there is no sign of Edmondson's grave marker because at the time cheap wooden caskets were used to bury African Americans. As the wood decayed it would cause the grave markers to sink into the earth.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mt. Ararat burial records of the period were lost in a fire, so his exact grave site is unknown.\n== Art Career ==\n[[File:Crucifix_ca._1932-1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|369x369px|\"Crucifixion\" ca. 1932-1937, carved limestone, gift from Elizabeth Gibbons-Hanson]]\nEdmondson entered the world of sculpture at the advanced age of about 60 years old in 1934. He reported that he received a vision from God, who told him to start sculpting: \"I was out in the driveway with some old sculptures of stone when I heard a voice telling me to pick up my tools and start to work on a tombstone. I looked up in the sky and right there in the noon daylight, he hung a tombstone out for me to make. I knowed it was God telling me what to do.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Jack|first=Lindsey|title=Miracles : the sculptures of William Edmondson.|last2=Pa.)|first2=Janet Fleisher Gallery (Philadelphia|isbn=0962150630|oclc=32664611}}</ref> He carved tombstones primarily from chunks of discarded limestone from demolished buildings, which were delivered to him by wrecking companies' trucks. A signature Edmondson tombstone reflects strong large lettering carved in the stone<ref name=\":1\" />. He began his career by working on these tombstones, which he sold or gave to friends and family in the community. Soon he began carving lawn ornaments, birdbaths, and decorative sculptures. In his yard hung a sign \"Tomb-Stones. For Sale. Garden. Ornaments. Stone Work W M Edmondson\". <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spires|first=Elizabeth|title=I Hear God Talking to Me|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2009|isbn=9780374335281|location=New York|pages=50-52}}</ref> \n\nEdmondson's work was influenced by his [[Christianity|Christian]] faith and his membership in a nearby [[Primitive Baptist]] congregation. His sculptures are straightforward and emphatic forms ranging from one to three feet in height, many sharing his unique religious symbolism. He carved figures of biblical characters, angels, doves, turtles, eagles, rabbits, horses and other real and fanciful creatures. His sculpture ''Noah's Ark'' stood tall in the middle of his backyard. It consists for four differently carved tiers of limestone and is the only architectural work that existed in his collection.<ref name=\":1\" />, He carved local community icons such as preachers, lawyers and school teachers, celebrities of the day who were important to the [[African American]] community, such as prizefighter [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]].<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio/william-edmondson/|title=WILLIAM EDMONDSON|work=Ricco Maresca Gallery|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> He also sculpted a number of popular figures such as First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Edmondson also created and a small number of nude figures.<ref>''[http://www.rawvision.com/books/outsider-art-sourcebook Outsider Art Sourcebook]'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009, p.70</ref> Most of Edmonson's carved figures consisted of faces carved on a spherical base, with a small mouth resting directly under a vertical nose, following to connect to the curve of the brow. Sometimes he would decide not to carve the eyebrows and would opt to make the nose broader. It is believed he did this to achieve racial inclusion within his collection of artwork<ref name=\":1\" />. Even with versatility of his artwork, the common characteristic of an Edmondson sculpture was the overbuilt-ness of the figures carved within or from the limestone. Intentional texturing ranging between smooth, chiseled, polished or rough was present throughout the make of each sculpture.<ref name=\":1\" />  The facial technique, overbuiltness, and range in texturing can be observed in Edmonson's most well known masterpiece ''Bess and Joe'' and further with ''Mary and Martha'' <ref name=\":1\" />.    \n\nEdmondson had a large audience in Edgehill and as many of his figures were on display not only in his yard, but in that of neighbors homes and gardens.  Around 1935, about a few years into this sculpting career, [[Peabody College]] art enthusiast, Sidney Hirsch, wandered though Edgehill and caught eye of Edmondson's vast sculpture collection.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Amico|first=Michael|url=https://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/distributed/E/bo27331575.html|title=Experience|last2=Mackintosh|first2=Lucy|last3=Jane Marshall|first3=Jennifer|last4=Peters Corbett|first4=David|last5=Situ|first5=Xiao|last6=Slifkin|first6=Robert|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2017|isbn=9780932171634|editor-last=Nemerov|editor-first=Alexander|location=Chicago|pages=102-133}}</ref> This is widely documented as Edmondson's \"discovery\" by [[Sidney Mttron Hirsch]]. Hirsch himself was a collector of African, Middle Eastern, and East Asian art and began to become one of Edmondson's greatest supporters .<ref name=\":3\" />  With this exposure, friends of Hirsch's and other fellow members of Nashville's elite bought Edmondson's sculptures for their homes, gardens, and offices, many of which were later displayed in exhibits at the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=Jennifer Jane|date=2017|title=Nashville, New York, Paris, and Nashville: William Edmondson, Mobilized and Unmoved|url=|journal=American Art|volume=31|pages=69-76|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> Of Hirsch's friends, Alfred and Elizabeth Starr, Alfred, a managing partner of a chain of movie theaters catering to the black community, and his wife Elizabeth, a painter, also became enthusiastic patrons and supporters of Edmondson's work.  They introduced Edmondson to several artist friends, including Starr's boyhood friend Meyer (Mike) Wolfe and his wife [[Louise Dahl-Wolfe]]. Dahl-Wolfe was a photographer who had recently begun work for ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' fashion magazine in [[New York City|New York]]. She made over a hundred of photographs of Edmondson's at work in his backyard shop, which she presented to the editor of Harper's Bazaar''.'' She attempted to publish his work but newspaper chain mogul [[William Randolph Hearst]], had a prejudice against showing Negro art as he seen them as nothing other than servants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/william-edmondson-down-home-artist-forging-beauty-stone|title=William Edmondson, a down home artist forging beauty from stone|work=aaregistry.org|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> <ref name=\":4\" /> She then brought Edmondson's work to the attention of fellow Tennessean Thomas Mabry and his boss [[Alfred Barr]], the director of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA)<ref name=\":1\" />.    \n\nEdmondson's career lasted for about fifteen years. His work never commanded large sums during his lifetime. In 1939 and again in 1941, he worked under the [[Works Progress Administration]], a government sponsored relief program that included artists. In the late 1940s, his health began to fail and his artistic production slowed. Edmondson professed to be uninterested in fame, and he appears to have struggled financially for the final years of his life. He is believed to have created about 300 works during his working lifetime.  \n\n== Exhibitions ==\n[[File:Bird_ca._1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|291x291px|Bird ca. 1937, carved limestone, gift from Margaret Z. Robson]]\nEdmondson was given a one-man show, the first by an African American artist, at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] from October 20th to December 1st 1937<ref name=\":1\" />. In 1938, through MoMA's influence, William Edmondson's sculpture was included in the \"Three Centuries of Art in the United States\" in [[Paris, France|Paris]]. Interest in his work on the national and international stage was short-lived, and he was viewed primarily as a novelty, or exemplar of the \"primitive\" race-memory of an untutored, naive old Negro stone carver. Locally, Alfred Starr continued to promote Edmondson's work to his artistic friends and acquaintances, who bought work directly from Edmondson's \"sculpture yard\" or through the local Lyzon Gallery. Starr introduced the famed modernist photographer [[Edward Weston]] to Edmondson in 1941, and Weston made several striking photographs of Edmondson at work in his shop and yard. Also in 1941, he received the only other solo show accorded during his lifetime, at the Nashville Art Gallery. \n\nAfter very sporadic exhibition through the 1950s and 1960s (mostly as part of \"folk art\" exhibits), collector [[Edmund Fuller]] wrote a biography of Edmondson which was published in 1973. His sculpture was included in the influential \"[[Two Centuries of Black American Art]]\" exhibition curated by [[Fisk University]] Art Department chairman [[David C. Driskell]] in 1976.  In 1981 the new [[Tennessee State Museum]] opened with a permanent solo exhibition with six of Edmondson's sculptures featuring loaned sculptures from Elizabeth Starr's personal collection<ref name=\":1\" />, and the essays in the accompanying catalog sought to elevate appreciation of Edmondson's work as fine art. Through the 1980s and 1990s Edmondson's sculptures were exhibited extensively, though often in the limiting context of the labels \"outsider\", \"folk art\", \"self-taught\", and \"naive\". In 1999, Nashville's [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art|Cheekwood Museum of Art]] mounted a major traveling retrospective exhibition and catalog that included in-depth biographical and critical essays on his life and work This exhibit also sculptures from Elizabeth Starrs personal collection of which she donated to the museum.<ref name=\":1\" /> A 2006 exhibition, \"William Edmondson, Bill Traylor, and the Modernist Impulse,\" paired Edmondson with another well-known self-taught artist and argued for Edmondson's acceptance as an artist without limiting labels. This exhibit displeayed twenty-one of Edmondon's sculptures which is the largest collection of Edmondson's art in the country<ref name=\":4\" />. In 2016 the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] received one of its largest gifts of folk art work from Margaret Z. Robson, among them were three of Edmondson's sculptures<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.edu/newsdesk/releases/smithsonian-american-art-museum-acquires-major-collection-self-taught-american-art|title=Smithsonian American Art Museum Acquires Major Collection of Self-Taught American Art|last=Baptiste|first=Laura|date=December 13, 2016|website=Smithsonian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nEdmondson's art is displayed permanently at the [[The Newark Museum of Art]],  [[American Folk Art Museum]], the [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]], the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], the [[Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum]], the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the Montclair Musuem in New Jersey<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\n== Legacy ==\nOn August 20, 2014, Mayor [[Karl Dean]] opened Nashville's first arts park, named in Edmondson's honor. The park, managed by the Nashville Metropolitan Development and Housing Agency, includes sculptures by [[Thornton Dial]] and [[Lonnie Holley]] inspired by the work of William Edmondson. The park is located in a traditionally African-American neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edmondson Park dedication officially opens city's first arts park |url=http://www.nashville.gov/News-Media/News-Article/ID/3178/Edmondson-Park-dedication-officially-opens-citys-first-arts-park.aspx |website=Nashville.gov |publisher=Metropolitan Government of Nashville and Davidson County |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |date=August 20, 2014}}</ref>  Even though the site of Edmondson's house at 1434 Fourteenth Avenue South is now a public school, it has been officially recognized with a Tennessee historical marker.<ref name=\":1\" /> About a few miles away, some of Edmondson's tombstones are on display at a local cemetery.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nSince his death, Edmondson's work has gradually come to be highly appreciated by critics and collectors, and his sculptures garner up to $70,000-$300,000 at auction<ref name=\":4\" />. Recently in January 2016, \"A Boxer\" sold at a private auction for $785,000 the highest price ever paid <ref name=\":5\" />.\n\n==Selected Recent Exhibitions==\n*Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, TN\n**''The Art of William Edmondson'' 1999 organized with the American Folk Art Museum, New York, NY\n** ''William Edmondson and Friends: Breaking the Mold, 2014''\n** [https://cheekwood.org/explore/art-4/exhibitions/past-exhibitons/edmondson-2017/ ''Visions from Above: The Life and Work of William Edmondson''], 2017\n\n== Collections with Edmondson Works ==\n\n*[[American Folk Art Museum]], New York, NY\n*[https://collections.artsmia.org/search/William%20Edmondson Minneapolis Institute of Art, Minneapolis, MN]\n*[https://www.nga.gov/features/exhibitions/outliers-and-american-vanguard-artist-biographies/william-edmondson.html The National Gallery of Art], Washington, DC\n*[https://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio-items/william-edmondson/?portfolioCats=126%2C22%2C23 Ricco Maresca Gallery, New York, NY]\n*[https://americanart.si.edu/search?query=Edmondson Smithsonian Museum of American Art], Washington, DC\n*[http://www.tnstate.edu/library/digital/EDMONDS.HTM Tennessee State LIbrary], Nashville, TN\n*[https://tnmuseum.org/temporary-exhibits/temporary%20exhibits/insearchofthenew The Tennessee State Museum], Nashville, TN\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*Thompson, Lovett, Freeman, McWillie, Gundaker and Sims, ''The Art of William Edmondson'', Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, Tennessee and University Press of Mississippi, Jackson, 1999\n*The WPA Guide to Tennessee, Compiled and Written by the Federal Writers' Project of the Works Projects Administration for the State of Tennessee, The University of Tennessee Press, Knoxville, 1986\n* ''Outsider Art Sourcebook'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edmondson, William}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Folk artists]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:People from Davidson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration workers]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American sculptors]]\n[[Category:American male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Janitors]]\n", "text_old": "'''William Edmondson''' (c.1874\u20131951) was the first [[African-American]] [[folk art]] [[sculptor]] to be given a [[one-person show]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in [[New York City]] (1937).\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Edmondson\n| image              = File:William Edmonson.jpg\n| caption            = William Edmondson sculpting in his backyard\n| birth_date         = December, 1874\n| birth_place        = Davidson County, Nashville, Tennessee\n| death_date         = February 7th, 1951\n| death_place        = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| othername          = \n| birthname          = William M. Edmondson\n| occupation         = Sculptor\n}}\n\n==Biography==\nWilliam Edmondson was born sometime in December 1874 on the Compton Plantation in [[Davidson County, Tennessee]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Thompson|first=Robert Farris|title=The Art of William Edmondson|last2=Lovett|first2=Bobby L.|last3=Freeman|first3=Rusty|last4=McWillie|first4=Judith|date=January 1, 1999|publisher=Cheekwood Museum of Art|year=1999|isbn=1578061814|location=Cheekwood Museum of Art|pages=3-14, 15-32, 33-44, 45-60|oclc=41932532}}</ref> He did not know the date of his birth because of a fire that destroyed the family Bible.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book |last1=Edmondson |first1=William |last2=Thompson |first2=Robert Farris |last3=Freeman |first3=Rusty |title=The Art of William Edmondson |date=1999 |publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi |isbn=9781578061815 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCOLisQ4eCkC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17 |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=10 things to know about William Edmondson |url=https://www.christies.com/features/William-Edmondson-10-things-to-know-8027-1.aspx |website=Christie's |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Edmondson was one of six children born to Orange and Jane Edmondson who had been and previously enslaved before they worked as sharecroppers. Due to privilege regarding race and color, mulattoes on the plantation were given more respectable jobs where as the Edmonson's  mainly worked in the corn fields and handled livestock. The Edmondson family worked on the plantation and earned a mere 12 dollars a month. During these times in the corn fields he would see \"angels in the clouds\" and believe it was God talking to him. <ref name=\":1\" />  Edmondson had little or no formal education. \n\n\nWhen his father died in late 1889,16 year-old Edmondson refused to continue to tirelessly work on the plantation and left to Nashville for work.<ref name=\":1\" /> He got a good job working at the expansive new [[Nashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis Railroad]] shops. After an injury sustained at the Railway shops in 1907, Edmondson took a job as a custodian at the Nashville Women's Hospital, where he worked until the hospital closed in 1931<ref name=\":2\" />. During this time Edmondson family officially resided in Nashville as his mother, Jane, was the last to leave the Compton Plantation. By age 39, his wages at Women's Hospital allowed him to buy a modest home and spacious lot in Edgehill, a segregated neighborhood in Nashville's Vanderbilt-Belmont area<ref name=\":1\" />.  Edmondson never married and he shared the home with his mother and sister, as well as, occasionally, other siblings, nieces, and nephews. With Jane's passing in 1922, Edmonson's sister, Sarah, soon became the woman of the house. It was said she would often hold family barbecues that consisted of laughter and storytelling.<ref name=\":1\" />  When the hospital closed in 1931, Edmondson picked up work at various part-time jobs and in his leisure, he could be found in his backyard sculpting and selling his vegetables.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\nIn 1948 Edmondson stopped sculpting. On February 7th, 1951 at age seventy-six, he passed quietly in his home in Nashville, Tennessee, where illness had confined him to bed for several months. As he was the last of his siblings to pass, his five nieces and seven nephews carried out his funeral service which was held the next day<ref name=\":1\" />. William Edmondson was buried in Mount Ararat Cemetery, now [[Greenwood Cemetery (Nashville, Tennessee)]], Nashville's oldest black cemetery. Today there is no sign of Edmondson's grave marker because at the time cheap wooden caskets were used to bury African Americans. As the wood decayed it would cause the grave markers to sink into the earth.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mt. Ararat burial records of the period were lost in a fire, so his exact grave site is unknown.\n== Art Career ==\n[[File:Crucifix_ca._1932-1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|369x369px|\"Crucifixion\" ca. 1932-1937, carved limestone, gift from Elizabeth Gibbons-Hanson]]\nEdmondson entered the world of sculpture at the advanced age of about 60 years old in 1934. He reported that he received a vision from God, who told him to start sculpting: \"I was out in the driveway with some old sculptures of stone when I heard a voice telling me to pick up my tools and start to work on a tombstone. I looked up in the sky and right there in the noon daylight, he hung a tombstone out for me to make. I knowed it was God telling me what to do.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Jack|first=Lindsey|title=Miracles : the sculptures of William Edmondson.|last2=Pa.)|first2=Janet Fleisher Gallery (Philadelphia|isbn=0962150630|oclc=32664611}}</ref> He carved tombstones primarily from chunks of discarded limestone from demolished buildings, which were delivered to him by wrecking companies' trucks. A signature Edmondson tombstone reflects strong large lettering carved in the stone<ref name=\":1\" />. He began his career by working on these tombstones, which he sold or gave to friends and family in the community. Soon he began carving lawn ornaments, birdbaths, and decorative sculptures. In his yard hung a sign \"Tomb-Stones. For Sale. Garden. Ornaments. Stone Work W M Edmondson\". <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spires|first=Elizabeth|title=I Hear God Talking to Me|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2009|isbn=9780374335281|location=New York|pages=50-52}}</ref> \n\nEdmondson's work was influenced by his [[Christianity|Christian]] faith and his membership in a nearby [[Primitive Baptist]] congregation. His sculptures are straightforward and emphatic forms ranging from one to three feet in height, many sharing his unique religious symbolism. He carved figures of biblical characters, angels, doves, turtles, eagles, rabbits, horses and other real and fanciful creatures. His sculpture ''Noah's Ark'' stood tall in the middle of his backyard. It consists for four differently carved tiers of limestone and is the only architectural work that existed in his collection.<ref name=\":1\" />, He carved local community icons such as preachers, lawyers and school teachers, celebrities of the day who were important to the [[African American]] community, such as prizefighter [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]].<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio/william-edmondson/|title=WILLIAM EDMONDSON|work=Ricco Maresca Gallery|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> He also sculpted a number of popular figures such as First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Edmondson also created and a small number of nude figures.<ref>''[http://www.rawvision.com/books/outsider-art-sourcebook Outsider Art Sourcebook]'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009, p.70</ref> Most of Edmonson's carved figures consisted of faces carved on a spherical base, with a small mouth resting directly under a vertical nose, following to connect to the curve of the brow. Sometimes he would decide not to carve the eyebrows and would opt to make the nose broader. It is believed he did this to achieve racial inclusion within his collection of artwork<ref name=\":1\" />. Even with versatility of his artwork, the common characteristic of an Edmondson sculpture was the overbuilt-ness of the figures carved within or from the limestone. Intentional texturing ranging between smooth, chiseled, polished or rough was present throughout the make of each sculpture.<ref name=\":1\" />  The facial technique, overbuiltness, and range in texturing can be observed in Edmonson's most well known masterpiece ''Bess and Joe'' and further with ''Mary and Martha'' <ref name=\":1\" />.    \n\nEdmondson had a large audience in Edgehill and as many of his figures were on display not only in his yard, but in that of neighbors homes and gardens.  Around 1935, about a few years into this sculpting career, [[Peabody College]] art enthusiast, Sidney Hirsch, wandered though Edgehill and caught eye of Edmondson's vast sculpture collection.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Amico|first=Michael|url=https://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/distributed/E/bo27331575.html|title=Experience|last2=Mackintosh|first2=Lucy|last3=Jane Marshall|first3=Jennifer|last4=Peters Corbett|first4=David|last5=Situ|first5=Xiao|last6=Slifkin|first6=Robert|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2017|isbn=9780932171634|editor-last=Nemerov|editor-first=Alexander|location=Chicago|pages=102-133}}</ref> This is widely documented as Edmondson's \"discovery\" by [[Sidney Mttron Hirsch]]. Hirsch himself was a collector of African, Middle Eastern, and East Asian art and began to become one of Edmondson's greatest supporters .<ref name=\":3\" />  With this exposure, friends of Hirsch's and other fellow members of Nashville's elite bought Edmondson's sculptures for their homes, gardens, and offices, many of which were later displayed in exhibits at the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=Jennifer Jane|date=2017|title=Nashville, New York, Paris, and Nashville: William Edmondson, Mobilized and Unmoved|url=|journal=American Art|volume=31|pages=69-76|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> Of Hirsch's friends, Alfred and Elizabeth Starr, Alfred, a managing partner of a chain of movie theaters catering to the black community, and his wife Elizabeth, a painter, also became enthusiastic patrons and supporters of Edmondson's work.  They introduced Edmondson to several artist friends, including Starr's boyhood friend Meyer (Mike) Wolfe and his wife [[Louise Dahl-Wolfe]]. Dahl-Wolfe was a photographer who had recently begun work for ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' fashion magazine in [[New York City|New York]]. She made over a hundred of photographs of Edmondson's at work in his backyard shop, which she presented to the editor of Harper's Bazaar''.'' She attempted to publish his work but newspaper chain mogul [[William Randolph Hearst]], had a prejudice against showing Negro art as he seen them as nothing other than servants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/william-edmondson-down-home-artist-forging-beauty-stone|title=William Edmondson, a down home artist forging beauty from stone|work=aaregistry.org|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> <ref name=\":4\" /> She then brought Edmondson's work to the attention of fellow Tennessean Thomas Mabry and his boss [[Alfred Barr]], the director of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA)<ref name=\":1\" />.    \n\nEdmondson's career lasted for about fifteen years. His work never commanded large sums during his lifetime. In 1939 and again in 1941, he worked under the [[Works Progress Administration]], a government sponsored relief program that included artists. In the late 1940s, his health began to fail and his artistic production slowed. Edmondson professed to be uninterested in fame, and he appears to have struggled financially for the final years of his life. He is believed to have created about 300 works during his working lifetime.  \n\n== Exhibitions ==\n[[File:Bird_ca._1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|291x291px|Bird ca. 1937, carved limestone, gift from Margaret Z. Robson]]\nEdmondson was given a one-man show, the first by an African American artist, at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] from October 20th to December 1st 1937<ref name=\":1\" />. In 1938, through MoMA's influence, William Edmondson's sculpture was included in the \"Three Centuries of Art in the United States\" in [[Paris, France|Paris]]. Interest in his work on the national and international stage was short-lived, and he was viewed primarily as a novelty, or exemplar of the \"primitive\" race-memory of an untutored, naive old Negro stone carver. Locally, Alfred Starr continued to promote Edmondson's work to his artistic friends and acquaintances, who bought work directly from Edmondson's \"sculpture yard\" or through the local Lyzon Gallery. Starr introduced the famed modernist photographer [[Edward Weston]] to Edmondson in 1941, and Weston made several striking photographs of Edmondson at work in his shop and yard. Also in 1941, he received the only other solo show accorded during his lifetime, at the Nashville Art Gallery. \n\nAfter very sporadic exhibition through the 1950s and 1960s (mostly as part of \"folk art\" exhibits), collector [[Edmund Fuller]] wrote a biography of Edmondson which was published in 1973. His sculpture was included in the influential \"[[Two Centuries of Black American Art]]\" exhibition curated by [[Fisk University]] Art Department chairman [[David C. Driskell]] in 1976.  In 1981 the new [[Tennessee State Museum]] opened with a permanent solo exhibition with six of Edmondson's sculptures featuring loaned sculptures from Elizabeth Starr's personal collection<ref name=\":1\" />, and the essays in the accompanying catalog sought to elevate appreciation of Edmondson's work as fine art. Through the 1980s and 1990s Edmondson's sculptures were exhibited extensively, though often in the limiting context of the labels \"outsider\", \"folk art\", \"self-taught\", and \"naive\". In 1999, Nashville's [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art|Cheekwood Museum of Art]] mounted a major traveling retrospective exhibition and catalog that included in-depth biographical and critical essays on his life and work This exhibit also sculptures from Elizabeth Starrs personal collection of which she donated to the museum.<ref name=\":1\" /> A 2006 exhibition, \"William Edmondson, Bill Traylor, and the Modernist Impulse,\" paired Edmondson with another well-known self-taught artist and argued for Edmondson's acceptance as an artist without limiting labels. This exhibit displeayed twenty-one of Edmondon's sculptures which is the largest collection of Edmondson's art in the country<ref name=\":4\" />. In 2016 the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] received one of its largest gifts of folk art work from Margaret Z. Robson, among them were three of Edmondson's sculptures<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.edu/newsdesk/releases/smithsonian-american-art-museum-acquires-major-collection-self-taught-american-art|title=Smithsonian American Art Museum Acquires Major Collection of Self-Taught American Art|last=Baptiste|first=Laura|date=December 13, 2016|website=Smithsonian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nEdmondson's art is displayed permanently at the [[The Newark Museum of Art]],  [[American Folk Art Museum]], the [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]], the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], the [[Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum]], the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the the Montclair Musuem in New Jersey<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\n== Legacy ==\nOn August 20, 2014, Mayor [[Karl Dean]] opened Nashville's first arts park, named in Edmondson's honor. The park, managed by the Nashville Metropolitan Development and Housing Agency, includes sculptures by [[Thornton Dial]] and [[Lonnie Holley]] inspired by the work of William Edmondson. The park is located in a traditionally African-American neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edmondson Park dedication officially opens city's first arts park |url=http://www.nashville.gov/News-Media/News-Article/ID/3178/Edmondson-Park-dedication-officially-opens-citys-first-arts-park.aspx |website=Nashville.gov |publisher=Metropolitan Government of Nashville and Davidson County |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |date=August 20, 2014}}</ref>  Even though the site of Edmondson's house at 1434 Fourteenth Avenue South is now a public school, it has been officially recognized with a Tennessee historical marker.<ref name=\":1\" /> About a few miles away, some of Edmondson's tombstones are on display at a local cemetery.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nSince his death, Edmondson's work has gradually come to be highly appreciated by critics and collectors, and his sculptures garner up to $70,000-$300,000 at auction<ref name=\":4\" />. Recently in January 2016, \"A Boxer\" sold at a private auction for $785,000 the highest price ever paid <ref name=\":5\" />.\n\n==Selected Recent Exhibitions==\n*Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, TN\n**''The Art of William Edmondson'' 1999 organized with the American Folk Art Museum, New York, NY\n** ''William Edmondson and Friends: Breaking the Mold, 2014''\n** [https://cheekwood.org/explore/art-4/exhibitions/past-exhibitons/edmondson-2017/ ''Visions from Above: The Life and Work of William Edmondson''], 2017\n\n== Collections with Edmondson Works ==\n\n*[[American Folk Art Museum]], New York, NY\n*[https://collections.artsmia.org/search/William%20Edmondson Minneapolis Institute of Art, Minneapolis, MN]\n*[https://www.nga.gov/features/exhibitions/outliers-and-american-vanguard-artist-biographies/william-edmondson.html The National Gallery of Art], Washington, DC\n*[https://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio-items/william-edmondson/?portfolioCats=126%2C22%2C23 Ricco Maresca Gallery, New York, NY]\n*[https://americanart.si.edu/search?query=Edmondson Smithsonian Museum of American Art], Washington, DC\n*[http://www.tnstate.edu/library/digital/EDMONDS.HTM Tennessee State LIbrary], Nashville, TN\n*[https://tnmuseum.org/temporary-exhibits/temporary%20exhibits/insearchofthenew The Tennessee State Museum], Nashville, TN\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*Thompson, Lovett, Freeman, McWillie, Gundaker and Sims, ''The Art of William Edmondson'', Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, Tennessee and University Press of Mississippi, Jackson, 1999\n*The WPA Guide to Tennessee, Compiled and Written by the Federal Writers' Project of the Works Projects Administration for the State of Tennessee, The University of Tennessee Press, Knoxville, 1986\n* ''Outsider Art Sourcebook'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edmondson, William}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Folk artists]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:People from Davidson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration workers]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American sculptors]]\n[[Category:American male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Janitors]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Edmondson"}
{"title_page": "Arko Pravo Mukherjee", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                 = Arko Pravo Mukherjee\n| image                = Arko2.jpg\n| caption              = Arko Pravo Mukherjee\n| birth_name           = Arko Pravo Mukherjee\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1983|005|19}}\n| birth_place          = [[Kolkata]], West Bengal, India\n| yearsactive          = 2012\u2013present\n| occupation           = {{hlist|Music composer|singer-songwriter}}\n| genre                = Bengali modern\n| website              = http://www.arkoworld.com/\n| background           = solo_singer\n}}\nDr. Arko Pravo Mukherjee is an Indian [[singer-songwriter]] working in the Bollywood film industry since 2012. ''[[Jism 2]]'' was his debut film as a music composer and lyricist.<ref>{{cite news |date=1 August 2012 |title= 'Jism 2' songs are not copied, says composer |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/india/jism-2-songs-are-not-copied-says-composer-493266.html |work=IBN Live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=17 April 2012 |title= Arko to compose music for 'Jism 2' |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/music/news-and-interviews/Arko-to-compose-music-for-Jism-2/articleshow/12700322.cms?referral=PM |work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=28 April 2012 |title= New Prescription Arko Pravo Mukherjee to compose music for Jism 2 |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/arko-pravo-mukherjee-to-compose-music-for-jism-2/1/186437.html |work=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=1 December 2014 |title= A quick four with Arko Pravo Mukherjee |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141201/entertainment-tvmusic/article/quick-four-arko-pravo-mukherjee |work=Deccan Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=7 November 2014 |title= Arko Pravo Mukherjee sings an EDM number |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/arko-pravo-mukherjee-sings-an-edm-number/ |work=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=10 February 2015 |title= Tips Music signs Arko Pravo Mukherjee for ten songs of their upcoming films |url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/biz/music/artiste/tips-music-signs-arko-pravo-mukherjee-ten-songs-their-upcoming-films-150210 |work=Radio And Music}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=13 February 2015 |title= On a high note: Arko Pravo Mukherjee |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/on-a-high-note-arko-pravo-mukherjee/ |work=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=8 August 2012 |title= Item songs don't work anymore: Dr Arko Pravo Mukherjee |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Item-songs-dont-work-anymore-Dr-Arko-Pravo-Mukherjee/articleshow/15400604.cms |work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=7 February 2015 |title=Signing A Deal |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.co.in/signing-a-deal/ |publisher=Box Office India |access-date=12 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222074025/http://www.boxofficeindia.co.in/signing-a-deal/ |archive-date=22 December 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=28 November 2014 |title= Nothing works beyond Bollywood, says 'Aaj Phir Tum Pe' singer Arko |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/nothing-works-beyond-bollywood-says-aaj-phir-tum-pe-singer-arko/story-oT7jLq630CZqKAWDG8AELI.html |work=Hindustan Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=29 December 2014 |title= 2014 Rewind: Bollywood musicians pick their favourite songs of the year |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/2014-rewind-bollywood-musicians-pick-their-favourite-songs-of-the-year/15873179 |work=MidDay}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=14 July 2012 |title= Music Review: 'Jism 2' has wonderful tracks |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/music/music-review-jism-2-has-wonderful-tracks-487734.html |work=IBN Live}}</ref>He is also known for singing several Bengali and Nepali music. According to Industry Experts and Bollywood Media Reviews, Arko is among the most promising new sensations in Indian Music and is also among the busiest Music Directors of Bollywood.<ref>https://m.imdb.com/name/nm3334275/bio?ref_=m_mn_ov_bio</ref><ref>https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/bengali/music/arko-pravo-mukherjee-is-a-married-man/amp_articleshow/66360261.cmsp</ref><ref>https://m.republicworld.com/entertainment-news/bollywood-news/kriti-sanons-bareilly-ki-barfi-movie-songs.html</ref><ref>https://scroll.in/reel/804588/composer-arko-mukherjee-raises-the-pitch-with-kapoor-sons</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nArko Pravo Mukherjee was born on 19 May 1983 to Dr. Apurba Kumar Mukherjee and Mahasweta Mukherjee in [[Kolkata]], West Bengal. He attended school at [[Don Bosco School, Park Circus]], Kolkata. Arko graduated with MBBS in 2007 from [[Burdwan Medical College]]. He completed his internship at [[Calcutta Medical College]] and then in 2008 he shifted to Mumbai to pursue a career in Bollywood film industry as a music director, singer songwriter.<ref>{{cite news |date=4 October 2015 |title= MEET DR DO MORE OF MUSIC |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/sunday-edition/sunday-pioneer/backpack/meet-dr-do-more-of-music.html |work=Daily Pioneer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=9 December 2014 |title=Rising Arko Pravo sets solid foot in Bollywood |url=http://archive.asianage.com/people/rising-arko-pravo-sets-solid-foot-bollywood-547 |work=The Asian Age |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222170522/http://archive.asianage.com/people/rising-arko-pravo-sets-solid-foot-bollywood-547 |archivedate=22 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2 December 2014 |title=A quick four with Arko Pravo |url=http://archive.asianage.com/music/quick-four-arko-pravo-147 |work=The Asian Age |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222170445/http://archive.asianage.com/music/quick-four-arko-pravo-147 |archivedate=22 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=2 November 2015 |title= Melody matters |url=http://www.asianage.com/music/melody-matters-504 |work=The Asian Age}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Hindi filmography===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| \n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"\n|'''Year'''\n|'''Film Name/Album'''\n|'''Song'''\n|'''Singer(s)'''\n|'''Notes''' \n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2012 ||rowspan=4|''[[Jism 2]]''<ref>{{cite news |date=14 July 2012 |title= Made in Calcutta: A DBPC boy has scored the soundtrack. Meet Arko Pravo Mukherjee |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120714/jsp/entertainment/story_15725199.jsp |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>  || Abhi Abhi (Male) || [[KK (singer)|KK]] ||\n|-\n|| Yeh Jism Hai Toh Kya<ref>{{cite news |date=3 August 2012 |title= \"Yeh Jism' is very close to my heart\" \u2013 Dr.Arko Pravo Mukherjee |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/3778/ |work=Bollywood Hungama}}</ref> ||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ali Azmat]]\n|\n|-\n|| Maula\n|\n|-\n|| Abhi Abhi (Duet) || KK, [[Akriti Kakar]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|2014 || rowspan=2|''[[Yaariyan (2014 film)|Yaariyan]]''<ref>{{cite news |date=27 December 2013 |title= I don't mind being part of a multi- composer movie: Arko Pravo Mukherjee |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Arko-Pravo-Mukherjee-takes-us-through-his-eventful-journey-in-Bollywood/articleshow/27976957.cms? |work=The Times of India}}</ref> || Allah Waariyan || [[Shafqat Amanat Ali]] \n|\n|-\n|| Zor Lagaake Haisha || [[Vishal Dadlani]] \n|\n|-\n|| ''[[Hate Story 2]]'' || Aaj Phir Tumpe Pyaar Aaya Hai || [[Arijit Singh]], [[Samira Koppikar]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Tamanchey]]'' || Dildara || [[Sonu Nigam]] ||\n|-\n||Dildara (Reprise) || Arko\n|\n|-\n|| ''[[The Shaukeens]]''<ref>{{cite news |date=23 October 2014 |title= The Shaukeens : On a Song \u2013 What started in the studio ended at a party |url=http://times